Republican strategy to resist Obama's re-election
Republican leaders justified their policies by combating voter fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth, arguing that cases of voter fraud in the United States are more rare than deaths from lightning strikes.
In addition, Republican lawyers counted only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in a decade.
One thing is for sure: these new trends will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
Unlike Canada, U.S. states are responsible for organizing U.S. federal elections.
That's why most state governments have passed laws since 2009 that make it harder to register or vote.
The phenomenon gained a new dimension after the November 2010 election, which brought Republicans 675 new seats in 26 states.
As a result, in 2011 alone, 180 bills limiting the right to vote in 41 states were passed.
New election laws require a voter to show a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws shorten the period of early voting, eliminate the right to register a voter on the day of the vote and take away the right to vote from citizens with a criminal record.
Before the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to show photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to introduce such a requirement.
The U.S. Supreme Court affirmed in 2008 the constitutionality of the Indiana law.
Republican authorities were quick to extend the practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have initiated bills requiring voters to show photo ID cards in 34 states.
It is important to note that, unlike in quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity card such as a health insurance card.
In fact, 11 percent of American citizens, or 21 million people who have reached the voting age required, do not have a photo ID issued by their state government.
In addition, five million new voters did not have such a document in 2012.
At the same time, the cost of obtaining the required identity card often exceeds a hundred dollars.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25 percent of African-Americans, 15 percent of people earning less than $35,000, 18 percent of over-65s and 20 percent of 18- to 29-year-old voters don't have the required photo ID.
But that's not all.
Voter students who are believed to be voting for Democratic candidates are not allowed to use their school's photo ID in several states.
But these same states allow members of fishing and hunting clubs, who vote mostly for Republicans, to use the voting certificates issued by these clubs.
Until 2004, no state required proof of U.S. citizenship to vote.
This is the first time such a requirement has been introduced in Arizona.
Since 2011, more than a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are apparently aimed at limiting the voting of Hispanics.
Two-thirds of Hispanic voters are believed to be voting in favor of the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers introduced laws in 2011 that abolish voter registration on polling day in eight states.
They have also restricted the right of individuals or groups to assist those who wish to register.
This restriction has not passed without consequences.
For example, during the 2004 elections, the voter registration campaign helped to list some 10 million citizens.
At the same time, measures taken since 2009 have led to a 17% drop in the level of new voter registration in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers have passed laws in five other states aimed at shortening the early voting period.
Thus, during the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of early voters were African-American, although the latter accounted for only 13% of the state's total voters.
The same thing happened with Hispanics.
Representing only 11 per cent of the electorate, they made up 24 per cent of the citizens who voted early.
Unlike whites, who, with 76 percent of voters, only 46 percent of early voters.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters are actively opposed to legislation restricting voter registration.
Several draft laws have been drafted by Democratic governors.
The most controversial laws were suspended under the intervention of the United States Attorney General.
This has partially limited the negative effects.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have enacted laws requiring photo ID.
However, the new rules that came into force will certainly make it difficult to exercise suffrage in the 2012 elections.
Critics of Democrats denounce the bias of the laws that were enacted, seeing them as an obvious focus on influencing the outcome of the 2012 election in key states.
A 2011 report by the Brennan Center shows that the states that passed the laws represent 171 of the 270 electoral college votes needed to win the presidential election.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes at the electoral level will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
There is only one certainty that these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
Prostate cancer screening: take a test or not?
In fact, the PSA test sometimes produces erroneous results, falsely and sometimes false positives, which lead to useless medical intervention.
Men, already reluctant to undergo dispensary, have something to doubt even more.
Take the test or not?
We asked the opinion of two experts.
Studies conducted in the United States have seen numerous cases of infection among the study groups, so the data are difficult to interpret and it is difficult to make any clear recommendations.
Another study, this time European, found different mortality rates in those patients who were screened and those who did not.
This study also showed, after 12 years of observation, that those who did not get a metestosis were 30-40% more likely to experience metastasis in those who did not.
Therefore, I would recommend taking the test from the age of 50, or from 40, if one of the straight relatives had prostate cancer.
African-American men are also at increased risk.
The key is to make the right decision once the cancer is detected.
Cancer can be both aggressive and sluggish.
The patient needs to explain the risk of his cancer, offering him possible options, without mandatory treatment of prostate cancer, which does not pose a danger to life in the long term, and making a choice, in these cases, in favor of active monitoring of the disease.
Today, many men who have been diagnosed with cancer will not be treated because their cancer is not aggressive and does not pose a threat to life.
We will offer them active surveillance, and if the disease starts to progress, we will start treatment.
Increasingly, we are pinpointing the criteria for deciding who should or should not be treated.
So I would recommend taking the test after all.
But it is also important to consult your doctor to determine whether or not to take this test.
In collaboration with the International Association of Urology, Movember has created a tool to evaluate the for and against the PSA test.
