Higgs boson in detail
Last summer, the news that scientists may have discovered the Higgs boson caused a real stir - and with good reason.
It is believed that this boson explains the mass of all particles in the universe, neither much nor little.
It is also the last particle that was predicted under the Standard Model - our best, or at least the "least imperfect" description of the nature and behaviour of matter - but which had not previously been detected by experience.
But physicists are not yet fully sure that it is about the Higgs boson.
We know, without a shadow of a doubt, that we are dealing with a truly new particle and that it strongly resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, new data presented this week at a major physical congress in Kyoto seem to confirm this, although some data are still lacking to be fully certain.
Let's imagine that we are talking about the Higgs boson, as the chances of making a mistake seem minimal, and we'll see what that means.
There is, in this world, one law completely inevitable, which reads that two things cannot end up in the same place at the same time.
There is no way to circumvent this rule, not even try too hard, otherwise harm yourself.
But while particle physics is a rather strange world, it turns out that it also has one law of this nature: the principle of Pauli's exclusion, which postulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time, if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" is, in general terms, in some of their characteristics.
On this basis, physicists divide particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find decent citizens called fermions who are prudently subservient to the Pauli principle.
In another bustling bosons, a vile gang of anarchists who have no respect for anything - at least for this principle, which means they can quietly end up in the same place at the same time.
According to the website (by the way, quite extraordinary) Particle Adventure Laboratory Berkeley, these bosons are divided, in turn, into two groups: mesons, which we will not talk about here, and "particles of force" through which the main forces of nature are spread and to which in some way refers to the Higgs boson.
These very bosons, it should be emphasized, are not all such exotic creatures as one might think.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to one incredibly banal boson: photon, or "particle of light" which is the "courier" of electromagnetic force.
In fact, when a single particle with an electrical charge accelerates or changes direction, it "violates" the electromagnetic field in that particular location, roughly like a stone thrown into a pond.
From this "disturbance" is born an electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared radiation, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon - and therefore one of the bosons of "power carriers".
A more stable field
The same thing happens with the Higgs boson, with the only difference being that in order for this boson to appear, another field, the Higgs field, must be "broken."
However, the Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, you need to reach very, very high energies, as if it were a frozen pond, the surface of which could shake only a very large stone.
That's why you need a huge particle accelerator like the one used in CERN - the Large Hadron Collider, which is a ring with a diameter of 27 km! To achieve such huge energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is also useful for explaining the relationship between the Higgs boson and the mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, interact, while others do not: a piece of paper, for example, will never be held on the fridge.
Similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that interact have mass, while others (like a photon, by the way) do not have it.
So what "can all this research bring," asks Ms. Plamondon?
In science, they are used to test the correctness of the Standard Model (CM), and it also allows physicists to find a discrepancy between observational results and CM predictions.
In addition, some of them are eager to see such a discrepancy revealed, because the slightest discrepancy can open the door to "new physics" and plug some holes of the Model.
The latter, it must be said, still has significant flaws, offering no explanation for gravity (oh!) or for dark matter, which forms about 80% of the universe (oy-oy!).
But so far, cern has not found such discrepancies.
consequences
The benefits of these studies for the everyday life of the average person are more difficult to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that it does not exist.
Look: in the early 1960s, the pioneers of laser research in Bell's labs could not even imagine what a revolution their work would cause.
They foresaw their applications in science, but nothing more.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Laboratories, where the laser was invented in 1960, and which itself developed the first continuous laser (previous were pulsed) in 1962, said that the laser was initially considered more like a "laboratory gadget".
Imagine...
And in addition, the application can be found for the toolkit accompanying the study.
For example, the same William Boyle during his optical research in 1969 developed a small light sensor.
This sensor, although not its original purpose, now serves as an "eye" for all the digital cameras of the world and has earned the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
This, of course, does not mean that the work of the Large Hadron Collider will necessarily change our lives, but it just shows, in fact, that everything can be.
Palliative care is the best way to die... | "Debt"
The Commission for a Dignified Death recently discussed the sensitive issue of the end of life.
Debate is about to resume, and a bill is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this crucial area.
"Debt" tried to take a closer look.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. Still lived alone in his apartment in Monterezi.
The prostate cancer that destroyed him from the inside gave him a two-year reprieve.
"I was given five years, I lived seven years," he says, between life and death, lying in bed in the shelter of the palliative care shelter Victor-Ghadbua in Belyoy, where he arrived the day before.
"But it's always a shock, you can't prepare for that," he says.
The disease does its job: an incredible weakness that prevents you from going to the toilet on your own and even eating on your own.
Sitting at the table, which is a delicious lunch, he gives up and agrees to be helped to take food.
He is awake, even manages to smile, talk to strangers who work around him, bring him medicine, lead him to the bath.
Courage before a common death.
"My greatest wish is to be cured of diarrhoea, it's humiliating," he admits.
A few hours later, the staff found a cure for the ailment.
"During our lives, we are taught that a man should urinate standing up," says Pierre Broder, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadboa shelter.
Regressing to a child's condition is an unbearable humiliation for some.
"It all depends on a person's ability" to accept decline," he says.
Because, according to many people engaged in palliative care, important events happen in the midst of this decline.
Patients who enter the Victor-Gadbua palliative care home are all with cancer.
Forecasts give them a maximum of three months of life.
At this stage, the team of doctors and nurses no longer provides care called "medical."
Ms A., 89, is most afraid of dying "in the mind of suffocation."
But the disease allowed me to get to know my children.
"I have good kids," she adds.
"I don't want anything else in life," she says, before allowing her to wear a mask that makes her breath-relieved.
She is still waiting for the next visit of her son, who came from Italy, in the coming days.
At the shelter, Victor Gadbua, with the help of a group of volunteers, provides body care and nutrition assistance.
This is palliative care that remains when nothing else can be done.
To make death more comfortable.
For every 11,700 inhabitants, there is one place in palliative care facilities.
That's not enough, considering that sooner or later we're all going to die.
Here life goes on in the best conditions that are possible, explains Dr. Christian Martel - one of the doctors of the shelter.
Whether it's physical, emotional or soulful comfort.
We'll agree to give the dying man a brandy or Pepsi rinse, whatever he asks for.
We no longer force diabetics to control sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night we brought beer to Mr. H., who died tonight.
In the morning, his son finished this beer in the legs of the deceased.
"We help loved ones as well as patients," says Natalie Savar, Director of Nursing.
In the shelter Victor-Gadbua not a single day is similar to the previous one.
Next to the 93-year-old, who enjoys his last meeting with his family in the yard, sitting on his pillows during the toast in his honor, tragically dies a young man 36 years, surrounded by his parents, his wife and two young children and tried everything to survive.
"In the last six months, three to five beds have always been occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45," says Dr. Christian Martel.
53% of patients admitted to the Victor-Gadbua shelter come from home, and 47% from the hospital.
The problem of access to palliative care
It is believed that 77 per cent of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, i.e. care provided to alleviate the suffering of patients entering the final stage of their lives, whether at home, in a hospital or in a shelter.
And some institutions, such as victor-Gadbois shelter and the Greater Montreal Home Palliative Care Society, specialize more or less exclusively in cancer care.
It is this large gap in the health care system that has led many palliative care physicians to fear the passage of a law legalizing euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Beginning in October, a manifesto signed by palliative care luminaries Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapuant has been circulating, indicating their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christian Martel, the health care system in quebec is not effective enough to ensure the right to high-quality palliative care before the transition to euthanasia is allowed.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who spent 14 days in the emergency room in terrible pain, and no one took the necessary measures to relieve them.
I fear that patients only want to die because they do not receive adequate care.
At the same time, many oncologists until the last day try to save patients, despite pessimistic forecasts.
Hopes for Helen Richard's survival were already minimal when she stopped gruelling chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping treatment, she told me she regretted stopping the fight," she said.
At the same time she told me that my days are numbered!
There is no omnis almighty care
Dr Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask for death are thanked by the medical staff for not fulfilling their request, after the palliative care team relieves their pain.
However, it should be noted that palliative care is not absolutely omnipotent in the fight against pain.
According to Elsie Monroe, director of palliative care at the Greater Montreal Society of Palliative Care, patients are not susceptible to pain relief in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, in which the patient sleeps until his death, either from time to time, or constantly.
We can no longer pretend that we do not know about these sufferings.
Increasingly, patients who fail to relieve pain will be able to have access to palliative sedation.
Pain patients always say the same phrase: "I want to die."
But it doesn't necessarily mean "I want to be euthanized," it means "I want to feel better."
