Pay and sell without the help of banks - with Bitcoin
The exact opposite of the current cash exchange, based on central banks, numbered transactions between receiving parties with commissions on their processing.
Moreover, as is often the case with these technologies, there is an obvious political vision: the belief that the current monetary system, consisting of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym) is simultaneously a virtual currency (but converted into dollars, euros...) and a protected BitTorrent-type exchange protocol that allows file sharing between participants of the same level.
About 200,000 operations have already been registered with 15,000 computers on the network.
Several thousand sites accept bitcoins for donations or as a means of payment.
The bitcoin exchange rate, having reached a high of $30 (23 euros) in June 2011, fell five months later to $2 before returning today to about ten dollars (the rates are listed on the bitcoincharts.com website).
Nothing special in comparison with the world exchange of real money or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) became interested in the system in its report on the virtual currency published in October.
He describes bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency," "competing with the dollar or euro" and "similar to conventional currencies."
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies, like the "credits" used to promote in a video game that are earned during the game or which can be bought (and sometimes exchanged).
The social network Facebook has also developed a similar system.
But exchange operations are always monitored and handled by any central body.
In Bitcoin, all nodes in the network are both account holders, auditors, currency issuers, buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two email addresses, similar to an email.
Only for each new payment can the user choose a different address, thus providing anonymity.
The informationset pertaining to this transaction is signed electronically using a dual-key encryption system.
The network can also verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is possible to verify that the bitcoins used in the transaction do exist in a public account book sent out throughout the network.
The key step is to register a new transaction in this book.
It goes through a mathematical problem sent to computers, which, like a temporary central bank, is privileged to add this new line.
We are talking about the hashing phase of the file, i.e. converting a large file into a digital signature, short and unique.
Computers "take" a new transaction and add a number to it before "hashing" all together.
The goal is to find a number that will give a unique digital signature (lots of zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, other nodes can easily verify that it is correct.
The transaction thus turns out to be unreactably linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification will change the digital signature.
If, with the aim of deception, the user would want to pay twice with the same money for the purpose of deception, only one of these two transactions would be confirmed by the network - and the other would remain unconfirmed, as they have different electronic signatures.
The computer that solves the problem receives 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, the award is regularly split in half, probably until the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divided to one hundred million, which leaves another reserve ...
The complexity of the task also increases with the increase in processing power.
The life of the network has already experienced the ups and downs.
Bitcoin service sites were attacked and bitcoins were stolen from reserves.
"The defect used does not concern the protocol itself," assures Pierre Noise, who recently launched Paymium, a company that makes payments with real money using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reported the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this disadvantage.
Big players like Wikipedia refuse to accept donations of this kind.
Others, such as the WordPress blog platform, allow them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the counting book and found that almost 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
"Giant sales" were announced in November.
"Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged," rejoices Jon Holmquist, who works at Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noise, another author of the currency manual, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as an operating network.
Its system, Paytunia, is the equivalent of a credit card (in real money) or contactless payment via mobile phone, but it uses Bitcoin to verify transactions that thus comes out cheaper.
The holder has better control over their personal data and can thus be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement for entrepreneurs who don't need to install new devices or software.
It is enough to give the address, which can be "photographed and recognized" by the phone, says Pierre Nooisa, assuring that he already has thousands of users.
There is a general tendency to revise hierarchical systems in favour of more horizontal systems.
"It will be some time before Bitcoin is approved, but 2013 could be a turning point," he predicts.
The ECB in its report suggests, by the way, to review the various risks considered to be elevated today, if the system is successful.
