The difficult birth of the Egyptian Constitution
This is a new risky move by President Mohamed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever on the issue of a constitutional declaration that temporarily gives it extraordinary powers, he has decided to play all-in.
Forcing everyone by surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on the final text the next day.
Exactly a week ago, the head of state gave the Assembly two additional months to finish the work.
It is soon two years since Egypt relied on a preliminary text that has been amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal contradictions.
This new initiative has only strengthened the division of the country.
According to his opponents, the President persists in his "autocratic delusions", continuing to "violate the word" and "to trample on the right".
In the camp, his followers believe that this is a way to end the institutional and political crisis by accelerating the transition process.
The referendum must be held within fifteen days.
A very short period of time, which forces the Brethren to abandon the intention to explain to the Egyptians the text, article by article.
For the president, it is also a way to restore public and democratic legitimacy, while discontent rages across the country.
Mohamed Morsi seems convinced that Egyptians will vote positively, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Moreover, the call for an accelerated vote is like an ultimatum to the Egyptian people: "Either you vote for my text, or I leave myself extraordinary powers", which are supposed to be completed after the adoption of the Constitution.
In this strange atmosphere, 85 members of the Constituent Assembly, mostly Islamists, voted yesterday for the text.
Most liberals did not respond to the challenge.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they slammed the door, feeling unable to convey their views.
Representatives of human rights advocates, religious minorities or civil society have done the same.
In order for the necessary quorum to be reached, 11 people, spare participants, were hastily added yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Unsurprisingly, in most cases the articles were voted unanimously.
Commentators, by the way, were amused by the fact that one of the few disagreements of the day arose around... time for prayer, as some members of the committee felt that the Constituent Assembly clock was incorrectly configured.
The text on which the vote was still taking place yesterday consists of 234 articles.
Subject to public attention, Article 2 ultimately remained identical to an article from the 1971 Constitution that stated that "sharia principles are the main source of law".
Salafist parties, for whom the introduction of Islamic law is a basic requirement, hoped to replace "principles" with "rules" that would allow for their stricter application.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a testament to their goodwill and respect for other members of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy" - answer liberals who see it only PR.
Because, in their opinion, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place through other articles.
They point in particular to article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular, in verifying compliance with Sharia law.
According to Sophie Pmier, an expert on Egypt, this is alarming because "people called to make decisions are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy."
We can observe the birth of the theocracy."
Many liberals, moreover, are excited by the fact that the next rector of this university seems to be much less moderate than the current one.
"At the moment there is no specific religious intervention.
With this constitution, we remain within the framework of civil law.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not ulema, but people with university education, some studied in the French system" - soothes Alexis Blow, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges that "there may be ambiguity around Article 220, as the terms used in it are borrowed from religious vocabulary.
This applies in particular to "fikhs" .Islamic jurisprudence.
And in the future, it may be a question of how competent civil judges are to rule on it."
In addition to its religious dimension, the text adopted yesterday has been criticized because it gives broad powers to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood claims that they have been significantly reduced compared to those under the old regime.
Another controversial point: the powers of the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, consideration of the defense budget will take place not in Parliament, but in the National Defense Council.
The trial of civilians in military courts will also not be prohibited, despite requests from human rights associations.
The latter also expressed concern about the text, which they considered detrimental to freedom.
Responsibility for blasphemy was maintained and insults were no longer prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of speech, and especially for freedom of the press.
In addition, none of the articles speaks more about protecting a woman, said Heba Moraef, of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive thing was the prohibition of torture in article 36.
A word that did not appear in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president was due to speak on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state, in turn, will take to the streets on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists are waiting for holy places, poop of the Earth and the sea of brine
The Promised Land combines the majesty of biblical truths, the modern comfort and pristine nature.
AIF highlighted five of the most important reasons to visit Israel.
Let's bow to the holy places
It is worth visiting the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is believed that all who enter this "coup" condescend to God's grace.
And Galileo is the place of Jesus' miracles: turning water into wine at the wedding, walking on water, calming the storm and filling the nets.
Here Jesus appeared before the disciples and after the resurrection.
But most of all the shrines in Jerusalem.
Believers here pass the Path of Sorrow or the God's Way of Jesus (in Latin - Via Dolorosa).
It begins at the fortress of Antonia - Pretoriume - where there was a court, and on the streets of the Old City leads to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on Mount Calvary - to the place of the Crucifixion, the Stone of the Anointing and the place of the burial of Jesus.
Here is also the symbolic Christian Pup of the Earth, symbolizing the salvation of mankind.
And the monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem was erected on the place where, according to Christian legend, grew a tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus.
In Jerusalem is also the holiest place for Jews - the Western Wall, left over from the temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
Traditionally, people of different confessions leave notes here with desires, which are then fulfilled.
Take a vertical journey
The ruins of the fortress of Massada were left from a secret refuge from enemies, which Herod the Great built in 25 BC for his family.
They are located on sheer cliffs in the mountains at an altitude of 450 m above the ocean level.
And only those who are fond of mountaineering can get to them in their own way.
The rest of this historic peak is delivered by a cable car lift.
And in the north of the country at an altitude of 1600-2040 m is the famous ski resort Hermon, which in the winter months - a huge influx of tourists.
A shuttle bus takes you from the foot of the mountain.
The total length of the ski slopes is 45 km.
According to ancient legend, on the top of the mountain supposedly lived pagan gods.
Visit unique museums
There are about 300 museums in this country.
You can't go to everyone in one trip.
But at least five of them, the most interesting, is worth a visit.
Among them is the Israel Museum, located near the Knesset (parliament).
It contains the oldest Kumran manuscripts, or Dead Sea scrolls found in the caves of the Judean Desert, and about 500,000 archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
It is worth visiting the Museum of Art in Tel Aviv.
His exhibition features paintings by impressionists and expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cezanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall, Picasso.
In Acre you can visit the museum-bath al-Basha, which is a few halls of ancient Turkish baths with imitations of visitors and bathers of the time.
In Caesarea, you should go to the unique private Rally Museum, where you can admire the sculptures of Dali and Rodin.
There are no guides and souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are categorically not accepted.
The fifth, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells the story of one of the most dramatic pages in history.
The most tragic section - a children's memorial - was built in memory of 1.5 million children killed in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You go into it and you find yourself in absolute darkness.
The stars flicker.
And the names of Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they died sound.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Healthier
The three main resort areas of Israel are located on the mediterranean, Red and Dead Seas.
Each of them has swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and aquariums.
Interestingly, the Red Sea bathe even in the winter months, because the water temperature there does not fall below 21 degrees Celsius, and the air warms up to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer, and there bathe all year round.
By the way, this most unusual sea in the world is at the lowest point of the planet - 417 m below the ocean level.
Azure water in it - brine, easily keeping afloat even those who do not know how to swim.
The landscapes around are unrealistically beautiful.
They come here to undergo treatment with salt water - rapes, and healing mud, and to treat health in dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes, to put in order the shattered nerves.
Touch the mysteries of antiquity
They are kept by an ancient part of Tel Aviv - the town of Jaffa on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea.
Through it passed the famous Sea Route connecting Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to legends, it was here that Noah built his ark, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom they lived a long and happy life.
Tourists love to wander through the narrow streets, named after the signs of the zodiac.
They say that if you touch the walls on the street of "his" sign, Fortune will be favorable.
In Jaffa you can meet newlyweds coming from all over Israel and even other countries for a photo shoot.
And in Caesarea - the city of King Herod - you can wander through the Roman theater, "take" the fortress of the Crusaders.
During the Roman period, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman prosecutors, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Tourist on a note
Going to Israel, do not worry about your imperfect English: in the country about 30% of the population know Russian.
It is better to take money for the trip not in euros, but in dollars, which are easy to exchange for shekels (now $1 - 3.8 shekels).
Urban transport is mainly buses, but Jerusalem has a high-speed tram, and Haifa is the only metro line in the country consisting of six stations and linking the Lower City with the Upper One.
In fact, it is an underground funicular.
Travel in all modes of urban transport costs 6 shekels, for which you can drive with transfers for 1.5 hours.
In Israel, according to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated on Saturday.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturday, markets, shops and public transport are shut down.
And on Sunday morning the working week begins.
Many cafes, restaurants and hotels only have kosher food that excludes pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes that combine milk and meat.
It offers a large selection of dishes of lamb and beef, soups and desserts cooked on coconut milk, traditional Jewish pasta hummus, a variety of sauces, balls of ground chickpea - falalel, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
But there are a lot of fattened cats, which are "walking on their own."
In the evening they can be seen sleeping even on the roofs of parked cars.
Purrs love crowded places and do not refuse treats.
Renting a car, depending on the brand, will cost from $37. (Hyundai Getz) to 188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Plus insurance - $15. a day.
A bike rental will cost 15 nis. a day.
Tickets to museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
The language of numbers
In 2012, Israel was visited by more than three million tourists from all over the world.
Citizens of the Usa, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine came to travel and rest the most.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists visited the Promised Land, which is 51% more than in 2010, before the cancellation of visas on February 9, 2011.
