Poland and space.
Last week, at a meeting of ministers of the European Space Agency, Poland was accepted by the 20th member of the European Space Agency as the second country from the countries of the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on September 12, 2008).
Poland began working closely with ESA in 1994 and over the following years became active in a number of agency projects.
But the path to space Poland began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish enthusiasts were engaged in flights to space, but this was not always met with understanding.
Let me remind you, for example, of the lecture of A. Sternfeld, who on December 6, 1933 presented ideas from his innovative work "Introduction to Cosmonautics" at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory.
Ideas of the young engineer (1905) left the audience indifferent, after several years Sternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomsky was interested in his work.
In 1934, Sternfeld won the Robert Esno-Peltry and Andre Luis Hirsch Award for Introduction to Space in France.
Dr. Jan Gadomsky (1899 - 1966), mentioned above, later became a great propagandist of astronomy and space.
He has published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and written a number of books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomsky became a well-known global propagandist of cosmonautics, and his contribution was appreciated by the fact that one of the craters on the back of the moon was named after him.
Already in 1925, a railway dredine equipped with a rocket engine was built in Poland.
Unfortunately, the author of this idea remained unknown, as well as the details of the project.
It is not even clear whether a rocket should have been used to disperse or brake the trolley.
Information about this dredus is known only from the press of that era.
In 1933, Polish artillery began to think about rocket arrows.
The study was carried out by the Armament Technology Section in collaboration with Professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustav Mokzycki.
From the surviving materials it is clear that the research has reached the stage of practical testing.
But with the arrival of German troops, the work was interrupted.
In 1937, the idea of a photovoltaic fighter rocket, proposed by engineer Rogozinsky, appeared in the specialized press, and the following year the work of "Air Torpedo Missile and Aerial Bomb Missile" by the author Leliva-Kzhivoblotsky was published.
Both projects were designed for the military use of rocket engines.
Before the war, all projects of military use of missile technology were carried out by the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated all the work.
The Committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation the work ended due to the outbreak of war.
The next scientific work on cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The society was first mentioned in the November 1954 issue of Problems magazine, which published four voluminous articles on astronautics.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotovich proposed to organize a society that will deal with space.
At that time, artificial satellite projects were already gaining momentum, and it was clear that space research was a promising industry.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Society of Astronautics (PAA) has been trying to join the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951), and in the autumn the POA became its active member.
And the following year, the first chairman of the POA, Kazimierz Sarankevich (1902 - 1959), became vice-chairman of the International Astronautical Federation.
He remained in this position until his death, which came in 1959.
Since 1956, the POA has made a significant contribution to the development of the highly successful RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna) meteorological rocket, which was the first Polish rocket to perform a scientific study.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957, and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket, capable of overcoming a distance of 1,800 m, was about 80 cm long and weighed less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959, a two-stage RM-2 rocket was tested at the Bledov wasteland.
The missile was about 1.4 metres long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the rocket was already able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 missile could overcome 14.5 km, and its task was to observe the high-altitude wind.
But in 1962 further development was suspended.
The heir to the first RM missiles was the Meteor-1 rocket, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (designated as Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed in size for the camera for scientific equipment.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space of 0.4 litres, the Meteor-1B was 0.34 litres and the Meteor-1C was 0.62L.
All three types had a maximum range of 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Aviation Institute developed the Meteor-2 rocket, and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket with a starting weight of 380 kg was able to bring a payload weighing 10 kg to an altitude of about 60 km.
Then versions of Meteor-2N and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland's accession to COSPAR (Committee for Space Studies) in 1960 and the establishment of the COSPAR National Committee two years later.
In addition, as part of the Intercosmos program, Poland participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978 Polish pilot Miroslav Hermashevsky became the second intercosmother after Vladimir Remek.
