"Operation Argo" Movie: When Things Get Worse, Call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of Islamist student demonstrators seized the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the ousted Shah Mohammed Reza Pahlavi, who fled after the revolution in the United States, who had been the patron of his regime for decades.
For the U.S. administration, the positive outcome of the situation was not supposed - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, because it could fundamentally undermine the confidence of allies in other countries.
However, it was not able to achieve the release of hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was later reinforced by a failed attempt to free the hostages by force.
The diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following negotiations brokered by the Algerian Government.
Their fate caused a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment at home.
Defeat in Iran contributed greatly to Jimmy Carter's defeat in the 1980 presidential election, which ended with the election of Ronald Reagan.
The film, directed by actor Ben Affleck, "Operation Argo" describes one of the episodes of the story that brought America small victories.
Shortly before the occupation of the embassy, six workers managed to escape.
After a difficult vicissitudes, they finished their way in the residence of the Canadian Embassy.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to take them away from Iran, and helped by an extravagant legend of cover-up, according to which they left on Canadian passports as members of the film crew, looking for a place in the country to shoot a sci-fi epic.
A combination of genres
The plan, which was invented by "evacuation" expert Tony Mendes, required Hollywood's cooperation.
To make the legend credible, specialized magazines wrote about the film project, arranged press conferences, a fictional production company had a real office.
Details of the operation have long been kept secret, the film is based on the memoirs of Tony Mendes.
Affleck's film is a special combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a real political thriller, the so-called "film-movieopus", the story of a successful idea, a scam - an example can be a number of films about Ocean's friends.
The film constantly changes moods - on the one hand, documented scenes from Tehran (the credits show the iconic historical photos of the events and how the same situations were demonstrated in the film - there are no big differences in this).
On the other hand, lightweight Hollywood passages intersect with irony and moderate exaggeration.
And then there are the scenes from the headquarters of the CIA and other institutions - men in suits discuss the situation at the negotiating table, on the stairs of institutions, on the phone ...
Ben Affleck has had a wonderful career.
From the ridiculed actor became a respected director, and his play ceased to be the object of ridicule.
"Operation Argo" is his third feature film, after the dark detective "Goodbye, baby, goodbye" (2007) and thriller "City" (2010).
At the same time, it is the first film Affleck, which is not filmed in the director's hometown - Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of the place at the same time refers to the qualities that elevated the director's earlier films above the Hollywood standard.
And Affleck shows it in "Argo," where Tehran "plays" Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place on the streets, during the reconstruction of real events - the opening scenes of the fall of the embassy impress with its clarity, which also conveys the emotions of confusion and unforeseenness that arise when somewhere suddenly changes history.
A similar effect Affleck and his colleagues achieve in fictional scenes (fake headquarters at a Tehran bazaar).
There are too many processes in too many places.
The director had to deal with the fact that the narration does not involve many exciting scenes of cinematic significance.
He works quite successfully with this few, sometimes something to think about - there all this comes out not so elegant (scene in which a phone call in America prevents the impending crisis at Tehran airport, and the chase on the runway look pretty far-fetched).
The downside of "Argo" is the absent-mindedness associated with the need to show too many events in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman as Hollywood colleagues are really very charming, but their characters would deserve more space, and they are not the only ones in the film.
Affleck's film lacks a bit of drama, it's a film that can be watched with moderate interest, appreciating the staging and retro style that recreates seventies thrillers.
But it's hard to capture.
However, this is enough to remind you of one, still in a certain sense, living history, and to testify to how exaggerated the ideas about the almighty and omniscient intelligence services.
