Architects MVRDV prove that real adventures are not only in the imagination - on the example of Speikenisse and his newly built Book Mountain - 2 photos
"I think this building is fun, it looks futuristic, we can finally see something interesting again," says Lisette Verhaig, a passer-by on the edge of the road.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT specialist at a nearby large enterprise, thinks, "No, this building is really beautiful."
But I ask myself: why do we need another library today?
Everyone has the Internet, iPad and e-books.
Now no one voluntarily goes to such old-fashioned libraries, right?
Speikenisse, a little-remarkable sleeping town near Rotterdam, holds an unusual record.
Its population of 80,000 people has the lowest level of education in the Netherlands.
To combat this unfortunate circumstance, a few years ago it was decided to contribute to general education and build seven fictional bridges, which are depicted on euro banknotes, in the form of picturesquely painted miniatures of reinforced concrete.
The success of this educational initiative has been modest.
And then the fathers of the city realized that they had the only opportunity to overcome the statistics: to build a library here!
Vini Maas of the Rotterdam Architectural Bureau MVRDV, a master of bold column charts and author of witty, sometimes even cynical buildings, treated the task with his usual calmness and appeared at a competitive audition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a grin on his face.
And while the members of the jury looked around puzzled and shrugged their shoulders, the brash Maas folded a pyramid of size from his original gift and concluded the speech in defense of his project with the following words: "Dear Citizens!"
Here it is, my suggestion: "Book Mountain" in Speikenis, the so-called Buquerenberg!
Nine years later, this mountain worth 30 million euros has grown.
It is part of a revitalization project that also includes an underground garage, supermarket, post office and several adjoining apartment buildings and townhouses for a total of 50 apartments.
In early November, Book Mountain was awarded the second prize of the 2012 Best Library of the Netherlands competition.
The project also participates in the national Dutch wooden construction competition in 2012.
Thus, the faceless suburb, which previously could not offer anything but a postmodern pedestrian zone and a surprisingly ugly town hall, the white facades of which suggest the idea of a dairy, has become richer on one modern piece of architecture.
But the most important thing is that the first public building of cultural purpose appeared in Speikenis.
The Long Road to the Book
First impression: book Eldorado under the cheese cap.
There is only one elevator in the center of the mountain range, because true fans of architecture and reading will prefer to explore this area on foot.
Glassed on all sides of the room - light and easily foreseeable, floors of burnt brick and elegant street lights unmistakably create the feeling of a public city square.
The urban environment is recreated perfectly.
The look is unwittingly looking for benches, dogs and football-playing boys and girls.
And everywhere - books, books, books.
"Usually bookshelves stand along the facades, and in the middle there is a large dark hall, usually uncomfortable and faceless," says Vini Maas.
We turned the classic space configuration upside down and pulled the reading area from the inside out.
The inner space of the book mountain is used skillfully: the center houses offices, an Internet library, a chess club, an environmental center and technical facilities.
Especially please black bookshelves, which serve as a wall finish, parapets, then ladder railings.
Their look, texture and smell are unusual.
Even sophisticated architects and civil engineers are lost in guesses, what is this unknown material.
"We wanted to work with secondary materials," explains Iop Trauborst, project manager representing the Speikenisse community, in accordance with the standard requirements.
And once at one agricultural enterprise in Friesland we met a suitable by-product of agriculture.
For many years, artificial fibrous material of millimeter thickness has been used as a lining for roots in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands.
It's cheap and saves time.
Thin textiles serve one or two seasons, after which it can be thrown away.
For the library, this canvas - for the first time in such volumes - was compressed into a panel four centimeters thick.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the so-called Landbauplastic (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous, durable material, smelling a bit like a new car and a little sneakers.
There are 105 steps to the summit.
Anyone who crosses the path of almost 500 meters will be rewarded in a literary cafe not only with fantastic views of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and wood ficus in pots.
They care about the atmosphere, and first of all about the correct humidity on the literary mountain.
New soul costs
"It's hard to believe, but this building, despite its many glass surfaces, is an exemplary project in terms of ecology," says Trowborst.
The heat of the earth is used to heat it.
Although the Book Mountain stands under a glass cap, even on clear days the sun gets inside only for a short time.
Wide cleen wood farms, perpendicular to the glass facade, give shade and take on most of the sun's rays.
The climate in the room is very pleasant.
The rest of the protection is provided by fully automatic roll curtains.
Stefan Spermon, the IT skeptic mentioned above, has already visited the new library.
Lisette Verhaig has already been here.
And also a teacher of traditional Chinese medicine Cynthia Bogarde, who called Bukenberg "the soul of Speikenissa, which has long been lacking."
Reason: A few weeks before opening, each resident received an invitation to donate one book from their own congregation.
These books were to take up empty space on the shelves of the not-yet-fully-staffed library - at that time it had 70,000 books.
The idea worked.
The shelves are filled to the top.
"There is nothing worse than a half-empty library," says architect Vini Maas.
"I think that thanks to our invitation, now every resident has some connection with this new home.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it only serves as a decoration.
Thus, MVRDV managed to solve the royal problem, which in professional jargon is called the creation of identity.
Speikenisse wrote his literary history.
And let them be very young and uneducated.
This is only the starting point for building an identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a more important role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the recognition of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on U.S.-European relations, Berlin is teetering on a narrow diplomatic path.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier in the week, Germany first made it clear that it would vote against the Palestinian bid for Observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained in the vote.
why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support israeli actions in Gaza.
Germany now needs to be cautious about its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I believe that it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained in a vote to impose a no-fly zone.
As a result, NATO held the proposal.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yes, it is.
The fact is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, namely moving from the policy, which, so to speak, was ruled by the United States, to the German foreign policy itself.
In addition, the situation is complicated by the fact that the Europeans do not have a coherent unified policy.
Thus, the Germans again find themselves between the two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe that so far they are only groping their role, but are on the way to a "more normal" foreign policy.
The kind of foreign policy that France or Great Britain has.
What exactly does "normal" foreign policy mean from a German point of view?
It is a willingness to take a position in the national interest that does not depend on the position of the United States or Its European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policy, i.e. on exports and ties with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are very different from those of other major states, and Germany must therefore protect its interests.
Have these economic interests affected the position in the Middle East conflict and the UN vote?
First, Germany has major markets in the Middle East, particularly in the Gulf states.
It therefore needs to be careful not to offend the public and the elites in Arab countries.
In any case, it plays a role.
But I wouldn't attach too much importance to it, it's not a completely one-sided relationship.
But in any case, it plays an important role in the calculations of the Germans.
Has Germany harmed its relations with the United States by abstaining in making important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I am sure that in Europe and even in the USA the understanding of the German position prevails.
So I don't think it was as dramatic as it was on the Libyan issue.
Perhaps Germany will even gain some respect in this way.
After all, it signals that it should be taken seriously as a player in the international arena and that its interests should be taken into account.
There are differing views on the Palestinian initiative in Europe.
The United States, by contrast, has clearly favored a veto.
Is there a divergence of opinion between the United States and many European states?
Because of American domestic policy, such differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama government at heart has a sufficient understanding of the European position.
But due to the local political situation, the government, of course, can not openly take such a position.
I believe that the significant differences of opinion are not as significant as it always seems.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, you'll notice that Obama is not at all enthusiastic about Netanyahu's policies.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close ties with Israel and the United States on the one hand and the position of the most important partner in the EU on the other?
I think that's what makes the situation so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there was a united, consistent European policy, but now it is not.
Therefore, they cannot take a broader approach and are forced to act instead on their own vision of the situation.
That's what they do with the euro.
I think that in the future Germany will take the lead in developing a common European position.
It is clear that it is not easy for Germany, if only because of its ties with Israel.
This topic has always been sensitive.
But I think it's clear to the Germans that they need to play a more independent role.
If Germany sees itself as an important international player, will it really take on the lead?
Or is the leading role still hard given to Germany?
Germany is not yet used to it, it is still always unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult to play a significant role.
Consider, for example, the euro crisis - every time Germany takes on an important role, there are a variety of anti-German feelings.
It's not easy for the Germans to deal with it.
Actually, it's an old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more difficult situation than the United States.
It should take into account a variety of neighbors and opinions, and this is not easy.
So, the influence of the United States in European politics is constantly weakening, but at the moment the EU does not fill this vacuum, who then remains?
The Germans will simply have to play a bigger role.
Even if you do not like it, unpleasant or strengthens dislike for you - such is life!
Stephen Szabo is deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institution where academics and political scientists from Europe and North America jointly explore the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, U.S. foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Trademark protection" in China: when Puma and Armani will suddenly become Chinese
Armani is a world-renowned brand, Polo Ralph Lauren - too.
But what is Armani Polo?
It is a completely officially registered name in China, which has nothing to do with the companies from which it is formed.
However, it will be protected until the owners of the original names are sued.
But even then it is unclear whether they will be able to defend their rights.
"It's becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to defend their trademarks in China," said Thomas Pattloch, an attorney with Taylor Wessing, a company specializing in trademark infringements in the Far East.
On my desk every week appears on a new case of this kind.
It is enough for imitators to add only a couple of letters to get the right to register their trademarks.
So from Gucci is Lu-Gucci, instead of Prada you can register Prada-Kny.
German companies, such as sporting goods manufacturer Puma, are legally copied in the same way.
Pattloch opens a folder with records from the trademark registration office in Beijing.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company registered there a trademark of zegna DF Puma, an artificial name, which also used the name of the fashion house Ermenegildo zegna.
It is known that the Chinese are world champions in copying and violating intellectual property rights.
In large cities there are multi-storey department stores selling almost exclusively fakes.
But Pattloch's case is not like that. On behalf of his trustees, he opposes that Chinese enterprises quite officially receive from the trademark registration office the right to use the name, which is already protected elsewhere.
The Chinese call it "ban minpai," a brand-passenger.
This word is associated with "ban daquan."
That's what they call women who hunt rich men.
Chinese authorities plead not guilty
"It's damaging to business, it needs to be addressed," Pattloch said.
"The brand is eroding, the unique position is being lost, the image is suffering very much."
The financial losses and procedural costs in the affected industries are in the millions, especially for expensive copied products.
According to market research company CLSA, China, with sales of 15 billion euros per year, is the third largest and fastest growing market for luxury goods.
However, it is difficult to remove questionable records in the trademark registry and it is expensive.
