Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the most important sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia and tripper (gonorrhea).
Frequent viral STIs include HIV, human papillomavirus, genital herpes and hepatitis.
Pubic pediculosis and scabies belong to parasitic STIs.
What are the main hit groups?
Syphilis and gonorrhea occur mainly in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute assumes that in at least four out of every five cases of syphilis reported in Germany, transmission is the result of sexual contact between men.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia infections, trichomoniasis, candidiasis (fungus), gonorrhea and human papillomavirus are common in heterosexual adults.
The prevalence of HIV among heterosexual adults is relatively low, but about 20 per cent of new HIV infections occur in this group.
Chlamydia infections are significantly more common among young people than among other populations.
According to European data, three quarters of all infections affect young people aged 15 to 25.
We also have a common human papillomavirus among young people.
How does the number of infections change?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are subject to mandatory registration.
The incidence of syphilis has more than doubled from 1,697 cases in 2001 to 3,698 cases in 2011, according to the Robert Koch Institute.
The number of new HIV infections has been declining since 2007.
In 2011, there were about 2,700 cases.
This is about one tenth less than in the previous year.
What symptoms indicate a sexually transmitted disease?
Infectious diseases can cause ulcers in the genital area, complaints about urination, discharge, pain in the lower abdomen, as well as bubbles or seals.
However, often they are not accompanied by pain and other symptoms and go unnoticed.
How can I protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but do not provide 100% protection.
After all, partially sexually transmitted pathogens can also be spread through contact infection and close physical contact.
Therefore, experts recommend regular examination, especially with frequent changes of sexual partners.
Early diagnosis can cure most STIs and avoid long-term consequences.
