"Someone likes aquavit more than rakfisk," Havard says.
This drink is able to interrupt the smell.
I'm trying a couple of pieces.
If you manage to carry a piece under the nose, then everything is not so bad - not much different from the portion of sushi, which you took with you for a long time in the bus.
Rakfisk is a Norwegian product from a completely different time, a time of poverty, when, even before the advent of refrigerators, fish in the autumn soaked in hermetically closed barrels of salt water.
Then in the deep winter, when the fish was already well and thoroughly fermented, it was extracted and, muting the perception of alcohol, consumed in food.
It is still in the memory of the last generation that thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work and emigrate mainly to the United States.
Now the population is growing rapidly - more than 13% are immigrants, who are attracted here by jobs, high wages and a developed social security system.
Residents of Sweden (a long-time rival, and not so long ago and much more affluent neighbor) come here to work.
Rakfisk is perceived as an important symbol, an indispensable, though somewhat foul-smelling element of Norway's past.
This is one of the most expensive local dishes.
On the other hand, everything is expensive here - a small glass of beer or a sandwich will cost you 9 pounds ($14).
Norway rarely appears in the world news, and the majority of the country seems to be satisfied with it.
People here are still reluctant to mention the name of Anders Breivik, the right-wing racist and extremist who last year shot and killed 77 men, women and children.
Without mentioning his name, the attack is called "the incident of July 22."
It is very difficult for Norwegians to believe that in their peace-loving country one of their fellow citizens was capable of such atrocities and murders.
At the heart of Norway's current well-being is the growth (since the early seventies) of one of the largest oil and gas industries in the world.
"However, oil is not the only reason for our prosperity," says Anna, our waitress, carrying trays of aged rakfisk, a woman with long blond hair and strikingly blue eyes, the embodiment of Nordic well-being.
We are such a people - as you call it - reasonable.
Like most Norwegians, she speaks English very well.
We don't like to show up, we're not braggadocio.
Norway is very careful with its oil - most of the oil and gas industry's revenues are invested in a special fund created for the benefit of future generations.
In the years leading up to the global financial crisis, when everyone was littered with money they didn't have, Norway thrixed all the costs.
"As long as you can ski in winter and go hiking in the summer, that's enough for happiness," says Anna.
"And there's rakfisk," she adds with a light-hearted laugh.
I'm standing in the snow in line for some food - rakfiska has had enough of me.
Here's a hamburger with elk meat - it's certainly exotic, delicious juicy meat.
But in the evening we will find even more of the same fish with an unforgettable smell.
My hotel hosts a special dinner dedicated to rakfisk, during which visitors vote to determine the best or perhaps the most fragrant fish.
There is a live TV broadcast, which shows the presenter in a bow tie, surrounded by plates with rakfisk.
It's like the Eurovision Song Contest.
"So, Thor-Jurgen, what is the grade you have put for the best fish there in your mountains?"
"Yes, Howard, here's our assessment."
Everyone laughs and applauds.
Someone falls from a chair, possibly by going through an aquavit.
Or maybe just inhaling the smell of this fish.
Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto faces a difficult start to his career.
As Mexico's newly elected President Enrique Pena Nieto prepares to take office, BBC correspondent Will Grant invites us to look at the difficulties he will face and the mixed expectations of his country's population.
Traffic in Mexico City is now in a particularly poor state.
The city is overloaded with traffic at the best of times, and since Monday steel barriers have been erected, cutting several key highways to the capital and causing traffic chaos.
However, this was not done to prevent people from getting to work from the suburbs, but to prevent protesters from getting to the parliament building.
On Sunday, Mexico's new president, Enrique Pena Nieto, will wear a presidential bandage and take the reins of government.
He faces a difficult task.
Mexico has achieved good economic performance under the administration of Felipe Calderon, which is now resigning, but the country is mired in a war on drugs that has already claimed some 60,000 lives in six years.
"My government is declaring to the people of Mexico its willingness to fight violence," Mr. Pena Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama in the Oval Office of the White House earlier this week.
I am going to propose a new security strategy that will enable us to achieve this goal.
Prior to such statements, Mr. Pena Nieto's political career had developed as governor of his home state of Mexico.
In his homeland, in the densely populated and vast state surrounding the capital, opinions about the new leader were divided.
Straight man
In the idyllic town of Valle de Bravo, for example, it is remembered with warmth.
Residents credit him with the revival of tourism, the development of the resort sector and the creation of infrastructure.
The city can be reached by one of the new highways built by Mr. Pena Nieto, which are strikingly different from the roads with potholes and pits that were previously on this site.
The plaques with his name hang on the modern building of the sports center and at the impressive interactive museum dedicated to climate change.
"We are pinning our hopes on real and serious change," said his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, a state congressman from the Pena Nieto-led Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI).
We look forward to the real and decisive changes that our country so desperately needs, particularly in the areas of security and economic development.
After 81 years in power, the PRI party was ousted in 2000 by Vicente Fox.
Congressman Olvera admits that after his 12-year absence from the Los Pinos presidential palace, the party has high hopes for Enrique Pena Nieto.
In addition, he refutes the accusations of incontinence made by the new president opposition.
He is very direct and very dedicated to the realization of his vision of the future of the country.
He is an excellent statesman, and, above all, a man who knows how to listen.
But in another part of the state, many people have a different idea of the former governor.
The municipality of Nesaualcoyot, also known as Ciudad Neza, is a stark contrast to the cobbled streets of Valle de Bravo.
Hidden under the overpasses of highways, it is in many senses a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the municipality are also severe in the metropolis.
Earlier this year, troops were deployed to subdue drug gangs in those areas; and violence against women is particularly acute here.
Dozens of bodies of murdered women have been found in a vacant lot near a vast landfill in the past two years alone.
More than a thousand women were killed in the state of Mexico during the governorship of Mr. Pena Nieto, far exceeding that figure in the notoriously violent city of Ciudad Juarez, whose name has become a household name when it comes to killing innocent women.
According to mr. Pena Nieto's opponents, it is at best that during his tenure as governor he has failed to deal with the problem of killing women.
At worst, his administration has been accused of ignoring the problem completely.
A resident of a concrete house similar to most of the houses in this dilapidated area, Irina Buendia can hardly hold back tears, showing me pictures of his late daughter Mariana Luna.
According to the official version of Mariana in 2010 committed suicide.
However, her family believes that she was killed by her partner.
"When I got to her house, it looked like her body had been washed before," Ms. Buendia recalled.
There were signs that she had been beaten, and her body was already covered.
Mariana's mother retells this story, and the portrait of her daughter looks at us from the wall, where it hangs next to the crucifix, which is written only one word: justice.
That, they said, was denied to the family.
"State officials treated me like an old gossip girl, a disgruntled troublemaker.
They want people to just take into their faith everything they say and keep quiet.
But it's wrong, it's not right, especially when there are so many violations and flaws around," she says.
Wearing a presidential dressing on Saturday, President Pena Nieto will take on the hard responsibility.
Over the past six years, tens of thousands of families in Mexico have been affected by violent crime, and the new President has promised to make tackling the problem a priority during his reign.
"I hope he will be exactly the same president as the governor," said Olvera, a congressman from Valle de Bravo from the PRI party.
However, this is what the families of the victims in Ciudad Nesa are most feared for.
Bradley Manning did not complain of ill-treatment, the prosecution said.
Prosecutors are trying to refute Bradley Manning's claims of poor conditions of detention.
During the hearing, increased attention was paid to Manning's stay in the military prison in quantico, Virginia.
The defense is demanding that the case be closed on the grounds that Manning's conditions were harsh.
A U.S. army private is accused of stealing several thousand classified documents.
On Friday, the prosecution tried to prove that Private Bradley Manning, accused of leaking classified material in U.S. history, had failed to take advantage of multiple opportunities to file a complaint of ill-treatment, which he said he had been transferred while in a military prison.
During cross-examination at a pretrial hearing in Fort Meade, Md., Military Prosecutor Maj. Ashden Fein said that records of Manning's weekly visits to the prison administration during his nine months in quantico, Virginia, did not contain complaints of ill-treatment.
The cross-examination, as part of the defense's motion to dismiss Manning's case on the grounds that the conditions of his detention were cruel and in themselves sufficient punishment, was conducted the day after Manning stated that he intended to commit suicide while in custody.
A military intelligence analyst arrested in June 2010 is accused of stealing several thousand classified documents while serving in Iraq.
The material was subsequently published online on The WikiLeaks website.
WikiLeaks did not confirm that Manning was the source of the information.
During Friday's hearing, Prosecutor Fein and Manning reviewed reports that were filled out after Manning's visits to the administration during his time in the cuantico prison, where he was held on a maximum-security detention facility from July 2010 to April 2011.
During the visits, prison officials asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When prosecutor Fein asked friday about the reports, Manning acknowledged that he views the treatment by the prison administration as "excellent" and the general conditions of detention as "very professionally organized."
The reports did not contain complaints of ill-treatment, even though Manning was directly asked about the conditions of his detention, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed verbal concern about these issues and that his administration officials had discussed these issues with him and said they would deal with them but did not record them in writing.
"They were recording "no problems" (after discussing my complaints), but that doesn't mean I didn't bring it up in the conversation," Manning said.
The military judge, Col. Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he had not complained about his mistreatment in January 2011 during a commission hearing examining suicidal intentions he had expressed in writing months earlier.
Manning said that during that meeting, he wanted to get the "injury prevention" regime removed from him and relaxed the conditions of his sentence.
The military leadership explained that a limited detention regime - a level lower than the suicide prevention surveillance regime - had been introduced to protect the prisoner as well as for the safety of others.
"I wanted to let the administration know that I'm ok to have them cancel the injury prevention regime... to make my life better from my point of view," Manning explained.
On Thursday, Manning testified about his arrest in Iraq and transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to a prison at the naval base in quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He reported that he had suicidal thoughts in Kuwait and that he had once lost consciousness because of the intense heat.
He explained that psychologically it is very difficult when you are not allowed to know how your fate is decided and what is happening in the outside world.
"My world has shrunk to Camp Arifjan base, to the size of my prison," Manning said Thursday.
"I thought I was going to die in this cage."
While in quantico, Manning, he said, spent most of his time in a small cell - at least 21 hours, and often more than 23 hours a day - all alone.
Manning says he was only allowed to leave a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, several items of clothing and glasses.
He says he tried to move because sleeping or even just lying in the daytime was forbidden by the rules.
According to Manning, while sleeping in his eyes he was constantly struck by the light penetrating outside the camera.
If the guards didn't see his face when he was in bed at night, he said, he was woken up and forced to roll over on his back.
Manning's attorney filed a formal objection to Manning's mistreatment in January 2011.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
Also on Friday, a judge asked Manning about a statement he made during his testimony on Thursday that after he was forced to sleep naked in his cell in quantico one night, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other inmates during a morning checkup.
Manning said he was unable to cover himself with a blanket during the inspection.
Responding to the judge's questions on Friday, Manning said he understood from the guard's order that he had to throw a blanket that he could cover for, but acknowledged that no one directly ordered him to leave.
On Thursday, Manning said he had been forced to sleep naked the previous night because of his attempt to show the officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning said he told the officer he could have used a rubber band of underpants or flip-flops to injure himself, but did not.
That night, according to Manning, his underwear, flip-flops and glasses were taken from the cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account what he went through during his incarceration and significantly reduce his sentence if Manning is found guilty by a military court, which is due to begin hearing his case early next year.
The defense said it plans to ask Manning to plead guilty to lesser offenses, while challenging other charges as excessive.
The resumption of hearings is scheduled for this weekend, and the prosecution is expected to insist that the conditions of detention have been justified.
The Pentagon alleges that Manning was held in quantico under rules governing the detention of detainees with the strictest possible regime.
Charges against Manning include aiding and abetting an adversary, illegally facilitating the release of data online, passing on national defense information, and stealing government property or documents.
If convicted on all counts, he could face life in prison.
My crisis of national self-determination is the story of an American of Mexican descent.
According to the author, many Mexicans were forced to leave Mexico because of the lack of opportunities to realize themselves.
Mexicans tend to blame those who have left because they remind the people of the country of difficult times.
Ruben Navarette believes that American-born Mexicans are torn between two cultures.
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I walked down the hallway for arrivals, approached the border control zone and froze on the spot.
Signs pointed to two queues: one for Mexicanos (Mexicans), the second for Extranjeros (foreigners).
I stood in front of them for a few seconds, not knowing where to go.
I grew up in central California, and I've been called a Mexican all my life.
It's just a conditional name, just like my friends in Boston call themselves Irish, and friends in New York consider themselves Italian.
Later I settled on the complex design of "American of Mexican origin."
But here I was in Mexico.
Here, in my grandfather's homeland, there was no need for conditional names or complex structures.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish well enough to ask questions or answer them.
But my vocabulary is poorer than that of native speakers, and I can't get rid of the American accent.
So I got my American passport and stood in line for Extranjeros.
I remembered this story a few days ago when the newly elected President of Mexico, Enrique Pena Nieto, visited the White House and met with President Obama.
On the agenda were the usual issues for the meetings of the presidents of these countries: immigration, drugs and trade.
President Pena Nieto was eager to talk about the recovery of the Mexican economy, which would allow Mexicans to remain in Mexico with the same success, rather than move to the United States.
He wants to conclude a partnership agreement with the United States and Canada and create a North American trading bloc like the European Union.
In addition, President Pena Nieto has vowed to continue the war against drug cartels in Mexico, but no concrete proposals have been made.
For Mexico, relations with the United States are a difficult and resentful question.
Most Americans never thought that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders to give up half of its territory at gunpoint.
But Mexicans think for centuries, not minutes, and see reminders of those events in everything.
Therefore, it is necessary only any statesman of the United States to speak at least a word of criticism in the direction of Mexico, in the press and among the elite of Mexican society immediately there are complaints that the Americans encroach on the sovereignty of neighbors.
And the descendants of Montezum are filled with militancy.
Mexico's relationship with more than 35 million Mexican-Americans living in the United States is the most difficult.
Want to talk about grievances?
There are enough of them.
In Mexico, there are winners and losers, people who find opportunities in this country, and those for whom there are no such opportunities.
In Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio, so many people of Mexican descent have only one reason: at some point in their family history, someone - a father or grandfather - has not been able to realize themselves in Mexico and has been forced to travel north.
Most often they were Mexicans of a certain type - dark, poorly educated, from poor peasant families.
We are their descendants, and we remember it.
In Mexico, it's not seen.
Today our life is the embodiment of the American dream, we studied in good schools and got a good job, but we will not forget that even this dream - American, not Mexican.
Our national self-determination is confusing and unclear, but we know which country to consider its own.
United States of America.
In addition, we know that most members of the Mexican elite and the ruling class do not like us.
We answer them the same way.
They see us as a reminder of humiliating defeats and treat us as second-class people, as fake Mexicans.
We don't speak Spanish well enough, and our ties with Mexico are not strong enough.
Our very existence for them is due to failures.
If our ancestors had succeeded in Mexico, they wouldn't have left.
We would not be behind the silk curtain now, having found a well-fed life in the United States, but having lost spiritual ties.
My wife was born in Guadalajara and moved legally to the United States as a child, and it reminds me that there are certain tensions between real Mexicans and Mexican-Americans - Mexicans have a clearer understanding of their national identity, and Mexican-Americans are offended.
She is a U.S. citizen and believes that she belongs to both of these countries.
At the same time, many of my fellow Mexican Americans do not feel any of them.
We listen to the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but we love Bruce Springsteen.
Getting the best of both worlds, you inevitably lose your roots.
In Mexico, we're Americans.
And in the U.S., they call us Mexicans.
Now, as I found out during my trip, as if our relations are already not complicated enough, some Mexican leaders and intellectuals want to restore relations with the diaspora.
They want Mexican-Americans to work as Mexican ambassadors and represent its interests in the United States.
We could tell our American friends what a beautiful country this is and how great it is to visit, and we could convince political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Yes, of course.
It won't work.
Too many offenses in the past.
And given the gap between rich and poor, rampant corruption and drug trafficking, many of us don't think this country is so beautiful.
Sorry, but deal with it yourself, amigos.
And that's fair.
If some Mexicans still cannot forgive the United States, as they did with Mexico a century and a half ago, they will have to accept the fact that some Mexican-Americans are still offended by the way their relatives have been treated in Mexico.
Yes.
I think we have more in common than I thought.
Old battles in the new Middle East
Ceasefire agreement between Israel and Hamas could be a fragile foundation for further peace
Is long-term peace possible between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East?
Another round of bloodshed leads to the conclusion that such hopes are futility.
Sounds, become familiar, meaningless arguments about who first started; Many buildings have been reduced to rubble; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis were killed; for the first time since the conflict, rockets fired from the Gaza Strip landed near the Israeli capital, Tel Aviv, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But while Israelis and Palestinians are hopelessly bogged down in their perennial conflict, the Middle East has changed.
This can be treated in different ways, but the events of the Arab Spring have swirled many well-established realities in a storm of rebellion, and Palestinians and Israelis have not been able to stay away from the vortex that has shaken the region.
Perhaps, as a result, their struggle will become even more bloody than before.
However, there are reasons to hope for a way out of this deadly impasse.
War without winners
At first glance, the current situation does not give cause for optimism.
Even if the ceasefire, signed on 21 November, is implemented, this week's clashes have only strengthened the positions of security forces on both sides.
Leaders of the Islamist movement Hamas, which came to power in the Gaza Strip in 2007, will claim that they forced Israel to retreat despite their losses.
Although some of the group's leaders were killed and 1.7 million residents trapped in one of the most densely populated and troubled corners of the planet, Israel has failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is increasing its popularity in the West Bank, another Palestinian territory now controlled by the more moderate Fatah movement.
Moreover, Hamas leaders may well conclude that time is working for them.
As the influence of Islamist movements in the Arab world grows, Hamas has new powerful and wealthy friends.
The resurgent regional leader Turkey, once Israel's closest ally among Muslim countries, has come out with the support of Hamas; it was followed by the example of the Richest and Dynamic States of the Gulf.
Rival Hamas supporters claim to have created an Islamist crescent around Israel - from Lebanon in the north, which is ruled by the militant group Hezbollah, to Syria, where increasingly pro-Islamist rebels are about to overthrow Bashar al-Assad's government, and on to Jordan, where the king's rule threatens Hamas allies.
The most significant change in the balance of power in the region occurred on Israel's southern borders, in the most populous and important Arab country, in Egypt, where the influence of the Muslim Brotherhood has been strengthened under President Mohamed Morsi.
Hosni Mubarak, who ruled Egypt for 30 years and was overthrown in 2011, was a secular dictator who did not pay much attention to supporting Hamas.
The Muslim Brotherhood, by contrast, is an organization very similar to Hamas, and their leaders are more prone to populism.
In future diplomatic arrangements, Hamas can become a significant player whose voice will not be silenced even by Israel and America.
At the same time, hardliners in Israel will come to the opposite conclusions.
In a military sense, Hamas was defeated.
Israel's Iron Dome anti-missile system justified the cost of its creation and successfully destroyed many of the rockets launched by Hamas.
Israeli citizens can sleep peacefully, at least for a while.
As far as diplomacy is concerned, the United States has remained true to its unwavering position; many European countries have also laid the blame for the latest round of violence on Hamas.
Another important factor is Israel's economic prosperity, especially under the Government of Benjamin Netanyahu, which has largely ignored the peace process.
Although some 30 Israelis have been killed by rockets fired from the Gaza Strip since 2004, Israel has succeeded in minimizing the problem of suicide bombings, partly through the wall that enters the West Bank - a large part of the unrecognized Palestinian State - and protects Jewish settlements that continue to expand despite the illegality of such actions under international law.
The position of Prime Minister Netanyahu, whose Likud party - in preparation for the January 22 elections - has teamed up with even more aggressive conservatives under Avigdor Lieberman's leadership is very comfortable.
What is the point of pandering to the Palestinians and giving them their own state?
If they surrender all power in the West Bank, will they not launch missiles towards Israel, as their brethren in the Gaza Strip do?
It is better to keep them behind the wall and severely suppress any attempts to raise their heads.
Perhaps hardliners will win; however, their calculations could be refuted by the Arab Spring.
While Islamists who come to power in Egypt and other countries do not have the warmest feelings for Israel, their priority will be internal problems.
Israel's defence budget is larger than that of all its Arab neighbours combined.
Waging war with a regional superpower is unlikely to help Arab governments strengthen their own economies.
The pragmatism of Egypt's president, Morsi, who worked with Barack Obama on the cease-fire, is a good sign and could mark the beginning of change.
Israel must, to say the least, take into account the long-term consequences of its policies.
As democratic changes in Arab countries onset, the denial of palestinian right to self-determination is a time bomb that will sooner or later explode in Israeli-occupied territories, like the bus that exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Repression was already undermining the foundations of the democratic order in the Jewish State, and the demographic aspect - the growth of the Arab population - only exacerbated those problems.
The bloody operations that take place every few years in the Gaza Strip to suppress the Hamas movement have to be paid for by the growing discontent of the international community.
Both sides need external momentum
The only solution that sane representatives on both sides, as well as much of the rest of the world and our newspaper, are relentlessly calling for: the formation of two States and Israel's concessions to territories in exchange for security.
The hope, which is not too impressive in the short term, remains to be hoped that the ceasefire will allow other countries to have a more effective influence on the parties to the conflict.
Egypt, which has long decided to cut off arms shipments to the Gaza Strip, and Turkey and qatar have more than ever taken advantage of the position to persuade Hamas to recognize the borders of the Jewish State adopted since 1967, taking into account the exchange of territories and the sharing of Jerusalem.
Other Arab countries should also make efforts to reconcile the Hamas and Fatah movements.
This would do more to create a Palestinian state than the upcoming UN vote, which could result in recognition of The Virtual Statehood of Palestine.
President Obama also has a role to play in putting Israel to the negotiating table.
During his first term, he never presented his own peace plan.
Since returning to the White House, he continues to show a reluctance to engage in a solution.
This is a catastrophically short-sighted position.
The United States has a vital interest in stability in the Middle East.
This is only possible in the case of a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
A law on unified packaging for cigarettes has come into force in Australia.
Warnings about the dangers of smoking and images of disease-stricken body parts are contrastingly highlighted on dull green boxes, the same for all brands of cigarettes.
Australia's first-ever law on the same type of cigarette and tobacco packaging came into force, replacing the logos and colours of different brands with the same box of dull olive colours with eerie images of disease-stricken body parts and images of children whose health was undermined by their parents' smoking.
In addition to the various pictures and inscriptions warning about the dangers of smoking, the only difference between the packs, introduced mandatory from this Saturday - the names of stamps that are printed in the same fine print.
These are the harshest conditions in the world for the registration of tobacco packaging.
The Australian Federal Government says the aim of the measure is to deter young people from smoking by depriving this bad habit of fashion status.
This decision was based on studies showing that people who did not start smoking before the age of 26, in 99 cases out of 100, never become smokers.
"Obviously, even at a very young age, children understand the meaning that tobacco companies try to convey by designing packaging," explains Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, referring to studies that have shown, for example, that the crown in the logo is associated with the idea of a princess in children.
Australia is one of the countries with the lowest smokers in the world, so these changes will not have much impact on the profits of multinationals, but other countries are already considering such measures.
Representatives of the tobacco industry strongly opposed the adoption of this law.
Tobacco companies argue that this will only increase the share of the black market, which will sell cheap and affordable cigarettes.
"This law will have serious consequences that are different from those conceived by its proponents," said Scott McIntyre, representative of British American Tobacco in Australia.
Manufacturers of counterfeit products from China and Indonesia will supply many more such goods for sale on the streets of Australia.
For some, on the contrary, the new laws contribute to the growth of business.
Sandra Ha of the small family-owned company zico Import Pty Ltd argues that the demand for cigarette cases and silicone cases that hide unpleasant pictures on the packaging has grown rapidly (virtually from scratch) since two months ago companies such as British American Tobacco, British Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost the case in the High Court of Australia, where they tried to appeal the law.
According to Sandra Ha, the company has already sold about six thousand products to wholesalers and expects a new batch.
It's a good business for us.
According to experts, the popularity of social networks among the very part of the population targeted by these measures is a potential obstacle to the effectiveness of such measures.
Following the adoption in Australia of a number of laws that made it illegal to advertise cigarettes and support sporting events, as well as prohibiting sellers from displaying cigarettes in a prominent place, tobacco advertising has moved to the Internet.
The Australian government has banned local companies and websites from advertising online, but it cannot restrict overseas sites.
"If you're a tobacco dealer and you only have this little loophole left, the idea of promoting your product online will seem very tempting," explains Becky Freeman, who studies public health at the University of Sydney.
Freeman notes an increase in the number of trademark reviews written on behalf of supposedly ordinary users on social networks such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
The question arises - is it really the work of an ordinary citizen who loves Marlboro cigarettes so much that he spared no effort and time and made a video, or is the advertising company behind it?
British American Tobacco's Australian division says the industry is now more busy adapting to the new rules than advertising.
Representatives of the tobacco industry even took measures such as sponsoring Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules: these States make claims within the World Trade Organization, claiming that trade has been unfairly restricted, despite the fact that all these countries' trade relations with Australia are very low.
The WTO decision is expected by mid-2013.
According to Tanya Plibersek, the government has discussed with other countries the possibility of adopting similar packaging laws.
In 2001, Canada was the first to introduce mandatory posting of photos warning of the dangers of smoking.
Now this rule is adopted in more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
The possibility of tightening the laws is being considered in the United Kingdom, New zealand, South Africa and India.
Many smokers in Australia defiantly disobey innovations.
These pictures don't bother me.
I just don't pay attention.
"Just snatch a cigarette and hide the tutu in your pocket," explains Victor El Haig, who buys cigarettes with a photo of a mouth tumor on a tutu.
Honestly, the only thing that can make me quit is my little daughter.
James Wu, head of the King of the Pack tobacco shop in central Sydney, claims that the same packaging has made it harder to place goods on shelves
"It used to take me an hour to unload a new batch, but now it's four hours," he complains.
"The government had to take and ban cigarettes altogether, we would then say: what to do, okay, it's over, close the store," he says, throwing his hands up.
To be bored in the world of electronic networks and constant connections is not so bad.
On this Thanksgiving, I suddenly had to spend five hours at the airport because our plane had mechanical problems and was replaced by another plane that we were waiting for.
So I had plenty of time to think about the nature of boredom.
I'm not going to lie to you.
Half a day at the airport waiting for a flight - it's really boring, and there are not much help neither books, magazines, iPhone, or even duty-free shops.
Recently, however, more and more scientists and specialists in children's development are speaking in favor of boredom.
They say that in certain situations it is not so bad for us and for our children to get bored.
This forces the brain to be distracted by interesting related topics, which may be conducive to creativity.
And since in today's world we are all constantly in front of some screen, the benefits of boredom pass us by.
Maybe we should strive for boredom?
Yes.
And at the same time, no.
We'll get back to that.
I used to, like many people, think that boredom is an invention of recent times, when people have more free time.
This is not the case, argues Peter Tui, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary and author of Boredom: A History Lively, Yale University Press, 2011.
"Actually, boredom boasts a very ancient history," he says.
On the walls in Pompeii found Latin inscriptions about boredom, dating back to the first century.
At the same time, the question of how we understand boredom remains open.
The problem is, says John D. Eastwood, an associate professor at York University in Ontario, Canada, that understanding and vision of boredom has often changed.
After studying research on the subject and asking a target group of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came to the following definition: boredom is when people "want but can't do something that would give them satisfaction."
The difference between boredom and apathy, he says, is that a bored person doesn't do something he wants to do.
I don't want to do anything when Apathy is apathetic.
The main thing about boredom, he says, is "a disturbance of attention and the associated deterioration of mood and the feeling that time is dragging slowly."
According to the description, boredom can seem very similar to depression.
However, Professor Eastwood argues that despite the possible link between these states, bored people see the causes of problems in the world and circumstances, and people experiencing depression see problems in themselves.
Sometimes we feel bored when we're really just having trouble concentrating on something.
In her study, "Unoccupied Mind: Determining Boredom from a Spotlight", published in the September issue of the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and colleagues refer to an earlier experiment, whose participants listened to a recording of a voice reading the journal.
Some participants also heard loud noises of a non-relevant television programme in the next room, others heard the same sounds at low volume, so that they could barely be disassembled, and the third group listened only to the recording of the voice without a sound track.
Those participants who heard low-volume TV noted that they were bored, more often than others - they found it difficult to concentrate, but they did not know the reason for this and attributed it to boredom.
When we try to focus on a difficult or exciting task, interrupting attention can be boring, says Mark J. Fenske, an associate professor of neurology at the University of Guelph, Ontario, and one of the authors of this study.
On the other hand, when we do something uninteresting, "for example, peering into the stream of products on the conveyor belt in search of marriage, distracting music can help avoid boredom."
It is believed, he continues, that when people start wiggle on a chair or draw a doodle on a piece of paper, they do so out of boredom, but now we know that in fact such actions just help not to relax physically.
"Research has shown that children who are not forbidden to fidget and twirl, learn better and memorize more information than children who are required to sit still," says Professor Fenske.
At some points we all feel bored: when the flight is delayed (as in my case), listening to monotonous speech, watching an uninteresting film.
However, different people show varying degrees of inclination to boredom.
In the 1980s, to measure such individual characteristics, researchers developed a special "scale of inclination to boredom."
To determine the assessment on such a scale, questions and statements are used, for example, "A lot of what I have to do is monotonous and monotonous" or "I'm too much interested, so there's no time for anything."
Using these questionnaires, the researchers determined that boys miss girls more often, says Steven Vodanovic, a psychology professor at the University of West Florida, "especially when there are a variety of external stimuli.
In general, however, teenagers are often bored.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of personal and social development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents 7-8 times a day.
It found that 32 per cent of teenagers said they were bored at school and during homework, and 23 per cent said they were bored outside of school.
At the same time, only 3% of parents said that they are bored.
Professor Larson notes that he has no data on what such data would be about boredom now, 21 years later.
However, he knows that "adolescence is the peak of boredom", mainly because children and adolescents are not allowed to fully decide what to do.
Let's go back to my original question: is boredom useful?
Sometimes not, because in extreme forms it can, as studies show, encourage people to take absurd and dangerous physical actions, risky gambling or abuse of certain substances in an attempt to get rid of boredom.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers have thought about the link between boredom and creativity, says Professor Vodanovic, who has devoted more than two decades to studying the problem.
"So our brain tells us to do something else; that's boredom," said Gary Marcus, a psychology professor at New York University.
However, this very brain does not always know what is better to do.
If you get bored and you direct that energy to playing guitar or culinary experiences, you'll make yourself better.
However, if you watch TV, you will feel better only for a while, and soon it will pass.
Therefore, if your child misses and you give him an iPad, he will stop getting bored, but he will not learn to fight boredom on his own or in any other way to manage his time and employment, - says Professor Fenske.
"And these self-regulation skills are used in a variety of situations," he says.
Your child learns not only to occupy himself with something, he also learns self-control in general.
I don't think boredom should be extolled in any way.
However, it is not worth considering it as something bad either.
Rather, you should learn to feel comfortable even outside the uninterrupted flow of action and technology.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"We see it in such a way that we need to experience boredom more often, even though boredom is an extremely unpleasant, unquenchable desire to do something meaningful," he says.
In fact, people tend to somehow disconnect from constant worries and just relax.
"In today's world, we are used to constant over-stimulation of the senses," he says, "and when silence comes, we get lost and don't know what to do."
It is not yet clear how the new law on marijuana legalization in Colorado will be applied
Anthony Orozco, a 19-year-old football team player and community college student in southeastern Colorado, is charged with a felony charge of what will soon be perfectly legal throughout the state: possession of a small portion of marijuana and the tube in which he smoked it.
Mr. Orozco says that one day in September he and his friends were in Lamar and were driving a car on the prairie near the Kansas border when they were stopped by police.
After a police officer found marijuana in the car, Mr. Orozco was subpoenaed for drug possession and possession of a drug device - minor offenses, each of which was due a $100 fine - and a court date was set.
"We are treated like criminals," Mr. Orozco said.
But is he a criminal?
As a result of the uncertainty that has been going on for weeks since the state of Colorado voted to legalize the use of marijuana in small quantities for entertainment, the decision of hundreds of small court cases depends not so much on the law as on the place of consideration.
Charges of minor marijuana-related offenses have already been dropped in hundreds of cases here and in Washington state, which has taken a similar measure.
Police stations have already stopped charging people aged 21 and over for possession of small doses, which will become legal as soon as the law comes into force in a couple of weeks.
But in Colorado's more conservative districts, prosecutors have decided to hear existing marijuana cases and continue to prosecute for possession of the drug.
At the same time, some cities, from denver suburbs to the mountainous regions of the West, are voting to prevent new, state-licensed marijuana stores from appearing in their locations.
"It's all so fast that I don't even know what to expect next," Daniel J. says. Oates, police chief in Aurora, east of Denver.
Regulators in Washington state are also baffled by scratching their heads.
They will have to form rules to determine how to license cultivation, processing, distribution and sale of marijuana, and all this must be done before December 1, 2013.
They say Colorado, for better or worse, is ahead of most other states in settling marijuana use issues, first for medical purposes and now for entertainment.
"Colorado has a more orderly market, so they will serve as a good example," explains Brian E. Smith, a spokesman for the Alcohol Regulatory Council in Washington state.
But now no one can do more, admits Mr. Smith, than put forward some proposals and hope that it will work.
"We don't have a real precedent that we can focus on," he says.
The Washington state bill, called I-502, will take effect on December 6 and plunge the state into a state of uncertainty for a year when the state licensing system is not yet available and marijuana ownership has already been legalized.
And there are still difficult technical aspects to be addressed during this period, such as how to strike a balance between the state's "adequate access" to licensed marijuana, with a ban on its trade 1,000 feet away from schools, parks, playgrounds and kindergartens.
"It will be particularly difficult to place licensed marijuana businesses in cities, particularly in Seattle and its suburbs," explains Ben Livingston, a spokesman for the newly formed Marijuana Legalization Center research group.
On 21 November, the Oates Police Chief of Aurora sent an e-mail to his subordinates saying that the city's prosecutor's office would no longer prosecute persons under the age of 21 for possession of a small amount of marijuana, and that the police would stop convicting people of the violations "from now on."
Oates Police Chief said police would monitor the city's compliance with rules governing medical marijuana growers and prosecute illegal drug dealers and distributors.
Weld County's attorney in northern Colorado, Ken Buck, is taking a stricter approach to the issue.
After the vote on the bill, he said that prosecutors would continue to prosecute marijuana possession, mainly to encourage users to take treatment.
At the moment, 119 people have been charged with possession of two or fewer ounces of marijuana, though many of them are charged with other violations.
"It is the responsibility of our agency to prosecute for acts deemed criminal at the time of their commission," Mr. Buck said in a statement.
The reaction has been mixed even in places like mesa rural district, where voters rejected a proposal to legalize marijuana.
Grand Junction Police, the largest city in the county, no longer prosecute adults for possession of a small quantity of the drug.
District Attorney Pete Hausinger upheld the decision, but also decided not to withdraw charges in already open cases involving marijuana possession.
"I believe that it is our direct duty to enforce the law until it changes," he said.
Although 55 percent of Colorado residents who voted supported the decision, it would not be easy to incorporate marijuana for entertainment into the state and legal system.
And the conflicting reaction of residents in different parts of the state laid bare the ambiguity of the attitude of local authorities to the state's experiment with marijuana.
"There is a cultural barrier for district attorneys in this matter," explains Sean McAllister, a Denver lawyer who represents those convicted of marijuana possession and a local representative of the National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws.
"They've been chasing people for so long that they can't really accept that it's not a crime," he says.
Colorado and Washington - the first states to treat a small amount of marijuana the same as alcohol - are destined to become an experimental field nationwide to test the very idea of legalizing drugs.
Proponents of legalization and state officials plan to expand the territory of the legalized trade, but at the same time they are cautiously awaiting instructions from federal authorities, who still plan to treat the sale and cultivation of marijuana as a federal crime.
Proponents of marijuana legalization hope the Justice Department will give in to the issue.
Despite several high-profile arrests of drug dealers and patients who used marijuana for medical reasons, the federal government has in most cases made the go-ahead for medical marijuana in Colorado, Washington and 16 other states.
Bureau of Drug Enforcement agents are unlikely to break into homes to confiscate a small bag of marijuana, but they are unlikely to turn a blind eye to state-regulated recreational marijuana stores that are allowed under the new law, said Kevin A. Sabet, a former anti-drug adviser in the Obama administration.
Some cities in Colorado did not wait for the actions of the federal authorities.
Even before the presidential election, some local administrations had approved a moratorium on new marijuana stores that would not have been able to open before a year later.
Last week, Montrose, a city in the western part of the state, put forward a six-month ban on the marijuana trade, which is likely to be approved next week.
"We don't want to be in a position where we're going to license someone, and then it's going to cause serious problems at the federal level," said Bob Nicholson, a city councilman.
Our city voted against this amendment.
And now we have a contradiction between the results of the local vote and what the state voted for.
There are still many unresolved issues.
Petronella Wyatt: I was survived from Oxford for being a Conservative.
The persecution of university students for their views did not begin today.
For as long as I can remember, I've always dreamed of going to Oxford University.
My father and older brother studied at Oxford and described it as the best educational institution in the world, a modern analogue of the antique symposium, laying two foundations of civilization - freethinking and tolerance.
And yet, after two weeks of studying at the history department of Worcester College, Oxford University in the late eighties, I packed my bags and left, which turned into the first real scandal of my life.
My father couldn't stand it and cried.
Friends were confused.
The Evening Standard claimed that I dropped out of college because I didn't like my classmates having sex in the next room.
Writer E. Norman Wilson joked that I left because I had to drink from chipped cups.
It wasn't really that funny.
I ran away.
Yes, I ran away because I was systematically bullied and intimidated.
Not because of my rather unusual name or the fact that I went to private school.
I was bullied for one reason only, and in this glorified cradle of enlightenment it looked like real barbarism and blind bigotry: my father, the late Woodrow Wyatt, was a well-known adviser to Margaret Thatcher, and I myself was a supporter of the Conservatives.
You may ask, why do we have to think about it now?
According to the latest data, the new generation of students, who adhere to the center-right views, are subjected to the same bullying.
This institutionalised and growing hatred of Conservative students at Oxford is so strong that last week a group of such students demanded the same protection of their rights as the one afforded to disabled, sexual and ethnic minorities.
Conservatives at Corpus Christi College In Cambridge say they are "often actively isolated, personally attacked and made to feel like unwanted guests" because of their political views.
They want to introduce an additional representative to the college's equal rights committee to ensure freedom of expression.
Their situation was only exacerbated by a recent BBC 2 documentary on student politics, "Wonderland: Young, Smart and Right," in which conservatives were portrayed as eccentrics and neo-Nazis.
The film featured Joe Cooke, the former president of the Oxford University Conservatives Association, who rides a Rolls Royce, wears a silver suit and a cane with a silver sledgeham over.
At other universities, conservative students complain that they are being made "scapegoats because of higher tuition fees."
Luke Black, 20, vice-president of the Conservatives Association of The University of Nottingham, told a Sunday newspaper that "there is a growing bias towards left-wing views in the university environment.
People who don't even know us think we are the brazen and violent children of rich parents."
Samuel Roberts, 21, a history student at Corpus Christi College, where the petition for increased protection was filed, calls the atmosphere "uncomfortable," while Stephanie Cherill, 19, the new president of the Conservatives Association at Oxford University, says the student club's attitude toward centre-right voters has deteriorated significantly.
"This is a threat to both the atmosphere of intellectual debate and just the normal lives of the club members," she said.
The first few weeks at Oxford I wasn't just in the minority, I was alone.
I got there in September 1986, a timid and shy eighteen-year-old girl.
Oxford was feverish with hatred for the Conservative Party.
A year earlier, the university had stripped former student Margaret Thatcher of her honorary degree by a vote because of budget cuts to higher education.
Even Stalinists would be uncomfortable in such an atmosphere.
In the first days of the freshman week, when students get to know each other and teachers, I felt for the first time what was waiting for me ahead.
I did not know that teachers not only looked past the bullying of conservative students, but also gladly took part in it.
Political issues - the miners' strike, privatization and the government's opposition to sanctions against the apartheid government in South Africa - penetrated through the wood-panelled walls of the auditoriums.
At my first seminar, I needed to translate the 18th-century French into English, and I wasn't ready for what followed.
"Miss Wyatt," said the teacher, now the late Harry Pitt, "please translate the first paragraph."
The text was given to me with difficulty, I stammered.
Harry Pitt was a very bilious man with a face that looked like a cake.
"Thatcherists fundamentally don't teach French or do they just have brains?" he asked.
Other students giggled.
There were tears in my eyes.
"I advise you to take a few initial French lessons in your spare time, unless you are very busy rotating in society," Pitt said.
I went back to my room completely miserable.
That evening in college, I sat alone at lunch; then someone patted me on the shoulder.
It was James, a second-year English student who introduced himself as a member of the University Conservatives Association.
"I know who you are," he said amiably.
"Unfortunately, this is the case:
anyone suspected of being sympathetic to the Conservatives will be bullied.
It's not easy for me, and in your case, they know your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so it's going to be harder for you.
Most of the fresh conservatives pretend to be Labour."
Later, at a local pub, I cowardly tried to be hypocritical.
I insisted that I didn't agree with everything Margaret Thatcher said.
The trick didn't work out.
The freshman of the Faculty of Philosophy, Politics and Economics, who himself studied at Eton, said: "You are the daughter of a fascist pig.
You're contagious."
Other students picked up his words.
I was spoiled, dirty.
"How do conservatives have sex? One of them asked.
"They're stabbing each other, aren't they?"
I felt the way homosexuals must have felt before the prosecution was abolished in the sixties.
Will I ever live a normal life in Oxford?
Or will I have to meet like-minded people only under the cover of night?
Will I be forced to become a Labour MP and hide my real beliefs?
The next three years began to seem hell to me, full of persecution and loneliness.
The only teacher in my college who did not hide his conservative views was Norman Stone, a professor of modern history.
He was hated not only for being a Conservative, but also for being Thatcher's foreign policy adviser and one of her speechwriters.
He didn't show up in college.
He despised him for his provincialism, pettiness and commitment to a Marxist-deterministic view of history.
In 1997, he took up a professorial position at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
"You won't be happy here," he told me.
I began to travel to Oxford from my parents' home in London, trying to find refuge among relatives and unbiased metropolitan friends.
I told my dad I hated Oxford and explained the reason.
He didn't believe me.
During his studies in the forties there accepted any political views.
"But it's the best university in the world," he said plaintively.
"They can't do that, but not in the city of dormant spires...
Even my Communist friends have always behaved impeccably."
His wet eyes were clouded.
"Don't make hasty decisions.
I'm sure it's just a joke.
You'll break my heart if you drop my university."
I was exhausted by the constant trips to London and my emotional defence was weakening.
My friend, also a conservative, could not stand the pressure and abandoned his convictions.
The following week, during a seminar, when another history teacher seriously called me "the enemy of the people," I decided to do the same.
In my heart, burning with shame, I confessed that "my parents brainwashed me" and called them "old fools."
The respite was short-lived.
The last nail in the coffin of my oxford career was destined to hammer my father.
At the time, he was writing two columns each week for Rupert Murdoch's publications.
My door was locked.
I didn't go out, and five minutes later my pursuers gave up.
When they left, I packed my suitcase and got on the first train to London.
I never came back.
You can call me a crybaby and a rag.
But at eighteen, no one should be the target of such anger and intimidation in the school.
It is all the sadder that it was Oxford, which not only produced fourteen Tory prime ministers, but to this day hides behind the undeserved reputation of a university that values equality and free-thinking.
"Valentino prefers elegance to fame"
On the exhibition "Valentino: The Master of Sewing", which opened this week in London, ABC talks with Nati Abascal, Fiona Thyssen-Bornemitz and other famous clients of the Italian designer
Somerset House, the former residence of the English queen Elizabeth I, is the only place in the British capital worthy of hosting an exhibition about Valentino Garavani.
The designer acknowledged this during the opening of "Valentino: The Master of Sewing," a triumphant retrospective exhibition that brings together more than 130 high fashion dresses created by his "home" over the past 50 years.
"I love this palace," he says with his unique Italian accent.
This exhibition is the final part of the story, the only character of which is "il signora" Garavani, but it could not be written without his famous clients.
Valentino always felt fascinated by the rare and distant world of nobility.
The first room of this exhibition, open until 3 March, is full of personal letters and photographs signed by the most noble aristocrats, from Princess Salima Aga Khan to Lord Snowdon, including Marie Chantal, Princess of Greece, and Margaret, Princess of Great Britain.
Valentino shows these personal memories as trophies of his social rise: from a humble tailor from the city of Voguera in northern Italy to the idol of the international "elite".
Being in love with the royal court is nothing wrong with that.
"At least they don't put out the cigarette butts of your gorgeous carpet, like some great pop stars do," says Baroness Fiona Thyssen-Bornemica.
In the 60s and 70s we both lived in the Alps and were good friends.
Valentino is an unparalleled host and welcomes guests with generosity and elegance.
"We all loved coming to his chalet in Gstaad," explains the ex-wife of "Heini" Thyssen, a close friend of forgotten beauties like Marella Agnelli or Eugenia Niarchos.
Valentino has always preferred the elegance of fame.
And despite this, he's a star.
Valeria Mazza, representing Valentino
Argentine model Valeria Mazza remembers a charismatic fashion designer.
One day we went to dinner at his house, it was after a fashion show in the Plaza de La Liga in Rome, many years ago.
Among the twenty guests were Sharon Stone and John F. Kennedy Jr.
Valentino's style was evident in everything - in every detail of his apartment, in its decoration, in food, in music.
"Valentino made each of the guests feel important and loved," recalls the "top model" whose work with the fashion designer began in 1995 during Paris Fashion Week.
"He never goes out of fashion because his sketches are real works of art," she concludes.
Pedigree Parade
Garavani's life is not a story of obsessions, but of falling in love with complete reciprocity.
He loves people with good upbringing and high titles, and they love him.
One of the galleries of Somerset House has been turned into a glamorous catwalk sixty meters long, which offers a change of roles: the visitor takes the place of models and has to defile on the catwalk, contemplating the "viewers" of dreams who sparkle masterpieces from Valentino, such as the dress that Jacqueline Kennedy chose for her wedding with Aristotle Onassis, a costume that Monica used in "The Nights" which belonged to Empress Fara Diba.
In this public, such names as Sybil of Luxembourg, Gloria von Thurn und Taxis, Mette-Marit from Norway, Rosario from Bulgaria or Sofia Habsburg shine from the models.
Nati Abascal and fashion designer, in 2006
Many of these clients say that the first Valentino - as the first love, "impossible to forget."
I remember him beautifully.
These were pants, a shirt, a vest and a jacket from the autumn-winter 1971-1972 collection.
"It was a gift he gave me," said Nati Abascal, one of the designer's muses.
"I prefer him to others for his femininity, for his great love for women, because he emphasizes our beauty," adds the former Duchess de Feria.
I love the colors he uses: they have a lot of light and they "fit" his face.
The proportions are perfect.
Princess and fashion legislator Patricia della Giovampaola d'Arenberg can't forget the first time she's dressed in Valentino.
When I was a teenager living in Italy, I dreamed that I would have an age and a reason to wear one of his evening toilets...
Finally came that hour in the late 90s.
I bought my first dress from Valentino to wear it for a holiday at my cousin's castle, Prince Edward de Lin.
It was a red dress, with a skirt with ruffles, a "corsage" in the crease and a strapless neckline.
"It was a dream come true," says Rodrigo d'Arenberg's widow.
"Valentino is indifferent to fashion, his passion is timeless," explains this Italian aristocrat, who lives between Paris, New York and Buenos Aires.
Princess D'Arenberg keeps her festive dresses from the fashion designer with "maximum care... because the dress is not just a dress, it is also a collection of memories accompanying it."
"King" of fashion
The grand finale of the exhibition at Somerset House - Marie-Chantal Miller's wedding dress for her wedding to Pavlos from Greece in 1995.
It took four months of work and 25 "girls" (as the fashion designer calls his seamstress) to make this outfit of ivory silk with inlaid pearls, twelve kinds of different laces and a train of four and a half meters.
According to journalist Suzy Menkes, the greatest authority of the specialized press, the dress is a high fashion mark of the late 20th century, "the return of clients from the highest light."
Intoxicated for many years by the "lifestyle" of the elite, now Valentino himself is its best representative.
Cavalier of the Grand Cross (the mark of distinction of the highest rank in Italy), The Cavalier of Labor, Commander of the Order of Arts and Literature, awarded the Legion of Honour, Garavani collected as many honors as any of his clients' spouses.
"I always had his finesse, his calmness, his neat and impeccable appearance," D'Arenberg recalls.
The last time I saw him was a month ago at a gala dinner at the Museo d'Ors.
He was sitting at a table with Countess Jacqueline de Ribe, my great friend.
"He was immaculate, time did not exist for him."
If the princess says it...
The hardest profession in the world: miners from Kawah-Ijen
For four euros Indonesian miners risk their lives and health by dragging 70 kilograms of sulfur to the top of the volcano on steep rocky trails
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others literally work in hell.
Among them is Anto Vijaya, one of 400 miners who make a living mining for sulphur in the Kawah Ijen volcano on the eastern Indonesian island of Java.
Every day, Anto descends to the bottom of the crater, where the sulphurous gas rising from the depths of the Earth freezes in contact with the air.
Chipping huge chunks of sulfur, the total weight of which can reach 70 kg, he puts them in two bamboo baskets, puts baskets on his shoulders and carries them up on a steep rocky road.
To the top of the volcano, the height of which is 2,386 meters, only 250 meters, but the exhausted loaders need more than 40 minutes to climb the turtle step, with difficulty keeping balance and carefully groping the way, so as not to stumble and fall off the cliff.
They know that one wrong move could cost them their lives, as happened to a tourist from France who fell off the cliffs of Kawah-Ijen a few years ago.
Miners from Kawah-Ijen earn 5 euro cents for every kilogram of sulphur they produce
Once at the top, they make their way between tourists who take pictures of them, as if they were monkeys from the circus and, wearily carrying heavy baskets, walk three kilometers to the scales, which the mining company placed a little higher, at an altitude of 1.850 meters.
We are talking about PT Kandi Ngrimbi, a company that has operated this volcano since 1960 and, better and not to say, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 euro cents) for each kilogram of sulphur.
It then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 euro cents) to petrochemicals, because it is common in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to whiten sugar.
"Since the norm is carrying 70 kilograms, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each walk," antho, who usually carries three daily shifts, explains to us.
He spends three hours on each of them and at the end feels broken, but they allow him to accumulate 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) by the end of the day.
While it seems like a miser for such a non-human effort, it's three times what he'd earn in the field.
"The fee for miners is very high by local standards, where coffee fees are paid 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) per day and the average monthly wage is two million rupees (167 euros)," explains the loader, who used to work as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
There his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day and the plot was not so heavy, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a town near the volcano, for a good reason, which in Indonesia is as crushing as the sulfur: "I married a girl from Bali, where only Hindus, and brought her to Java to convert to Islam."
Anto has asthma, he breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly, and his eyes water because of toxic gases
At the age of 27, Anto spent three years risking himself in Kawah Igen, whose sulfur had already begun to affect him despite the presence of a mask and special glasses.
He has asthma, he breathes with difficulty, constantly coughs, and his eyes get water because of the toxic gases that the volcano emits.
This is the price he has to pay to achieve his dream.
"I'll work for two more years because I want to open a shop or learn Spanish or French," he promises in more than acceptable English.
Punished by life, this nice and intelligent young man might be a tour guide, waiter or porter at the hotel, but instead he does the work of a mule.
Sharing a dirty wooden hut with other porters, he gets up every day at two o'clock in the morning, because the sulfur does not cease to flow out at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the midst of darkness.
Defying the shadows, Anto descends into the crater, illuminating his way with a small lantern connected to his helmet, which he himself bought with his own money.
About 400 porters carry baskets of sulfur on their shoulders from the bottom of the volcano
Despite the high profits, the mining company has not mechanized sulphur production to save costs and does not provide any equipment to porters who work on their own account and with such deprivations.
In fact, they don't even get a portion of the 30,000 rupee (2.5 euro) photography fee, which, along with the entrance ticket for 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros), the guards of this reserve charge tourists who come to take pictures of the volcano and its mules.
"This work is for cattle, not for people," says Badrusin, a stocky porter for 42 years who has spent three decades on Kawah-Ijen since he left college.
Able to lift up to 110 kilograms, he assures that he will tolerate work "as much as he can" because he needs money for the education of his three children between the ages of 18 and 10.
I'm not retiring, I'm going to die here, because a volcano is my whole life.
Although sulfur burns the throat and burns the eyes when the wind suddenly changes and catches the miners in dense columns of smoke coming out of the volcano, they are so hardy that no one complains of their severe diseases ... more serious, obviously, than their usual breathing problems, osteoarthritis, knee pain and sores on the shoulders, which deformed under the weight of baskets.
Balancing the basket on his back, Unainik can now only lift 50 kilograms in his 53 years.
Every day he and his comrades carry 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks transport to a warehouse in Tamansari, covering a distance of 18 kilometers along a narrow path among the thickets.
"I'm not retiring, I'm going to die here because the volcano is my whole life," Unaynik says, opening his mouth wide, which lacks several teeth.
Of his five children, the eldest, 30, also works as a sulfur vector.
Time passes, but poverty perpetuates from generation to generation one of the hardest things in the world: what human mules from Kawah-Ijen do.
