It spends $1,300 a year on policies to encourage citizens to have more children.
The state package for couples and parents provides up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and provides tax credits.
But all this has low efficiency.
Singapore is a rich and high-tech city state in Southeast Asia, also known for its conservatism and strict public control.
The birth rate in Singapore, according to its National Population Authority, is currently at 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was below 2 - which is known as the replacement rate - was in 1976.
So why don't Singaporeans have more children?
Tang Wei Ming, director of policy for couples and families at the National Population Administration, said the reason was "improved education" and a "broader range of career opportunities."
"This has allowed people to have a wider range of options in terms of life goals and priorities other than weddings and family building," she explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to an increase in the number of bachelors and to the postponement of marriages and births, resulting in a decline in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, immigration policies, which aim to dramatically increase immigration to counter population declines, are causing outrage among local people.
There are websites in Singapore that thrive on the barely concealed xenophobia of many new immigrants, especially the Chinese, who have been criticized for keeping wages low and not being integrated.
