UNASUR summit ends without the announcement of the Lima Declaration
The 6th presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) ended today in Peru without the publication of the Lima Declaration, which was previously announced and theoretically signed by seven mandatory participants.
Efe has repeatedly attempted to gain access to a document signed at the 6th meeting of UNASUR heads of state and government, but sources from the Office and the Presidential Administration indicated on the front page that it would be handed over after the closure, but then confirmed that it would be published on the Peruvian government's website at some point.
When asked about the text, they indicated that the contents had been provided by the President of Peru, Rillanta Humala, during brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to information about the Summit was limited all the time.
During the day it was only broadcast, in the press room, a video of the presidential assembly without a sound with the message "closed meeting, sound is forbidden".
A small number of information circulating among reporters was passed on by the press secretary of some UNASUR governments who attended the meeting, but not the Peruvian one.
The only document circulated during the day was a list of participating presidents, which angered hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who asked for more information.
Subsequently, the Administration of the President of Peru sent an e-mail to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it was a statement by Humala, not an official document that concluded the summit.
Peru hosted the III Summit of the South American and Arab Countries (ASPA) last October, and the so-called Lima Declaration, which had previously been announced, was not circulated at that time, despite the insistent demand of the press.
On the official ASPA website, you can check that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to ensure that transmission systems for all journalists were provided, but they limited the receipt of information as much as possible.
The summit also concluded with a joint decision by Chile and Peru to accept the verdict of the Hague Court, which would settle a territorial dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Olyanta Humala, and Chile's Sebastian Piniera, gathered for a regional meeting and ratified that they would abide by the decision of the International Court of Justice, which begins hearing statements by both sides in The Hague on Monday, as part of the accusation that Lima has brought against Santiago.
"We will abide by and implement a decision that will clarify the differences that we are currently presenting to this international court," Umala said, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was, is and will be a country that respects international law, peaceful resolution of differences, pacts and international tribunals," Piniera added, and greeted with a handshake between Umala and the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation by both Presidents that they will submit to the International Court of Justice came just after Colombia challenged this week's Bogota Pact, under which it accepted submission to the verdicts of that international court following a decision on maritime borders with Nicaragua, which it deemed erroneous.
The summit took place in the absence of the president of Brazil, Dilma Rousseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chavez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina' Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, whose membership in UNASUR has been suspended since 2011 following the impeachment of its former president, Fernando Lugo, did not attend the meeting.
The host president, Illanta Humala, was responsible for opening the discussions in the morning and closing the summit, just after noon Lima time.
The head of state read the final document, in which he said that 16 agreements were adopted and directions for 31 projects among South American countries were approved, the amount of the proposed investment amounted to 17 billion dollars.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the UNASUR countries would take "important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which we are expanding residency agreements".
He said that action was being taken to improve "cooperation against citizens' insecurity and against organized transnational crime, action to increase the availability of medicines, low-cost Internet access in all corners of South America and taking into account the cumulative and effective risks of natural disasters".
Since Europe is in crisis, "economic unification (Latin America) should not have a triumphant basis, but should serve to expand our production framework and foresee a better future for our cities," Umala added.
"We decided to give privileges to a group of 31 iconic projects that will improve the connectivity of South America' spaces, especially in the rural and border areas... uniting our countries and forming new economic schemes," the Peruvian president said in a statement.
Among those projects, he mentioned that five belonged to Peru and were limited to cross-linkings to its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and the two aimed at a greater link with Ecuador, but he did not provide further details.
The final document also touched on the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in that country will serve as its re-accession to the Union of South American Nations," from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, to be united and to have good relations between its neighbours, was another topic highlighted at the summit.
In that sense, Colombia's president, Juan Manuel Santos, said before entering a regional meeting that he hoped to meet with his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico City for respectful talks on the maritime dispute in the wake of the verdict of the international court challenged by Bogota.
"The day after tomorrow (Saturday), I may meet with President Daniel Ortega," Santos said.
"We will revise all these ways, they are not mutually exclusive, including the pact with Nicaragua will require discussion with Nicaragua," he said.
"With President Ortega, I hope I can tell him that we will cope with this in the most civilized and respectful way possible," Santos added.
Santos and Ortega will meet on Saturday in Mexico City, where they have a presence at the inauguration of the country's new president, Enrique Pena Nieto.
Also during the summit, the bloc's defense ministers met tentatively to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which aims to strengthen dialogue and unanimity on the issue of protecting the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay form UNASUR, although the latter's participation is suspended.
Peru has a temporary presidency in the regional bloc.
