AIDS deaths today are the result of late diagnosis
Fabrizio was 21 years old when he was told that his AIDS test had tested positive.
"It was like I was stunned," he recalls the moment, despite the doctor's tact.
The young man hid it from his family.
Deciding to cope with the disease on his own, he wanted to learn about it as much as possible. And his efforts were justified - he has already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
Fabrizio is one of the "oldest" patients in the HIV department of the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), where he was admitted in 1994, having overcome many obstacles.
He has been diagnosed with human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years. In the early 1990s it would have been hard to believe - there were too few treatment options, too little knew about the disease, too biased against the sick.
So, even the director of the clinic of the Mexican Institute of Social Protection did not want to say goodbye to him, "because he had a cut."
In other words, in those days to have AIDS was a sentence.
Now it is possible to survive with this syndrome and do it without impairing the quality of life.
However, without knowing about their disease, still many people come when the virus has already caused damage, "exhausted" their immune system and they suffer from opportunistic infections.
Thirty-one years after the advent of AIDS in the world, at least after the first reported cases, "the great achievement at the moment is that the survival of the patient who starts treatment in a timely manner and the survival of the general population are exactly the same," said the head of HCG's HIV department, Jaime Andrade Villanueva, citing the fact that this information was confirmed in April this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
An infectious disease specialist and HIV/AIDS expert, Andrade Villanueva explained that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is not a sentence, but the duration and quality of life depend on the degree of immune system damage available to patients at the beginning of diagnosis, with better life expectancy for those who do not use drugs: up to 30 years with the number of 200 CD4, and up to 50 years when reported 500 CD4.
Simply put, the above means that those who are diagnosed with HIV-positive at the age of 25, according to these terms, "maintaining control, will be able to live without problems up to 75 years," he explained.
To measure this progress, it should be remembered that the life expectancy of Mexicans today is an average of 76 years.
Although mortality has declined significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people dying of AIDS has fallen from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (UNAIDS annual report), it is also true that 60 per cent of patients in the national database have died since the advent of AIDS.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and 187 deaths had already been reported by May of this year; however, it is claimed that there has been widespread access to antiretroviral drugs since 2005.
- Why are there still fatalities?
- Personally, I think that the problem is not access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's the way it is in our hospital.
For at least the last 12 years we have had no shortage of medicines, the problem is that patients come very late because they do not know about their infected condition, that is, in the later stages of the disease.
He cited devastating figures: "Nine out of ten patients come when they already have some kind of opportunistic infection; what needs to be done to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to make a diagnosis at an earlier stage, and therefore samples must be provided for detection on a massive scale, for all the people who ask for it."
In his proposal, experts and officials of the State AIDS Prevention Council in Jalisco (COESIDA) agree, as well as patients themselves, such as Fabrizio, who applied for a check-up at a private laboratory, prompted only by the fact that his friend did it and, despite his young age, he was already at the stage of AIDS and even suffered from Kaposha sarcoma, a cancerous tumor which is one of the common complications.
Things change when you know you have AIDS.
Some people think they're going to die, and they don't want to know.
"If I die anyway, I'd rather get drunk three times a week," they say. But not in my case.
There are positive changes, I eat well, do exercises, take medication.
To date, his parents only know that he has suffered from cancer.
I live a normal life like any other.
"I work, I have a lot of occupations, I travel, I have an active sexual life, but with mutual responsibility, I care about myself and the other person," said Fabrizio, who agreed to share his personal life with MILENIO JALISCO, to encourage those who are now, in the context of World AIDS Day, feeling fear.
Let them check if there was a risk of infection, let them know as soon as possible whether they are HIV-positive, so better, and if they already have a diagnosis, let them know that they can live like any other person, being responsible.
This message summarizes the theme of the fight against AIDS in this 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
There is a great gap between health programmes and ordinary citizens, according to Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who has tackled HIV-related issues.
And the biggest thing is prevention.
In places dedicated to this task, "there was actually an increase in the distribution of condoms, we used to be given one or two, now we are given packages of one hundred, and that's very good, but it turns out that there are those who still do not have access to a condom," he said.
Among the most vulnerable to new infections are adolescents.
"Why do you need them?" is a popular question, with echidna and condemnation, from social workers, school counselors, pharmacy staff and health care workers who don't want to hear teenagers, the propagandist assured.
I propose to change this inefficient distribution; that condoms should not only be behind the counters and that a hundred of them should be in vending machines in public toilets in places frequented by young people.
This is not an encouragement of promiscuity.
It's not about paying for beer and a motel, Gov. Emilio Gonzalez said when asked if it was possible to distribute condoms under his leadership.
"It's not sexuality, it's best to make condoms available to those who already practice sexual activity," he said.
Key data in Jalisco
There were 13,435 total cases (12,158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV).
The state ranks 4th in the national ranking for new and cumulative AIDS cases and 13th in HIV.
92% of infections refer to the sexual pathway, 6% through the blood and 2% to the perinatal pathway.
It is estimated that 50,000 people can live with HIV, as there are between 4 and 5 people who do not know about it for one reported case.
