"I've played many basketball roles throughout my life, including several at the same time, like when I was president of BSN, general manager of the National Team and president of the federation in the 90s," Reyes recalled during Primera Hora's visit to his home in Bayamon, where he has lived with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
"Basketball was my life."
Reyes is not exaggerating by making this statement.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photographs and memorabilia collected over his long journey, bear witness to this.
Bayamon in the heart
With the greatest emotion he keeps those who remember his way through the Cowboys, starting from the mid-50s as a player until 1982, when he turned 15 years old as a co-agent or contract agent.
"These were my best years, which I enjoyed the most because I had the opportunity to be part of eight Cowboys championships since 1967, as an agent, co-agent or manager.
There were many years of joy, including five championships that took place from 1971 to 1975.
And then I said goodbye to one in 1981, the year Jerome Minsi made his BSN debut.
From that moment on, "Cuco" Ortiz, who was a great administrator, was in charge," Reyes said.
